n[[Category:Cities in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:B\u1eafc Giang| ]]\n", "name_user": "Megumisbs", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%E1%BA%AFc_Giang"}
{"title_page": "Gaudapada", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}} \n{{Infobox Hindu leader\n|name       = Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da\n|image      = Shri Gaudapadacharya Statue.jpg\n|caption    = Adi Guru Shri Gau\u1e0dap\u0101d\u0101ch\u0101rya\n|birth_date =\n|birth_place=   \n|birth_name =\n|death_date =\n|death_place= \n|known       =\n|religion   = [[Hinduism]] \n|founder    = [[Shri Gaudapadacharya Math]]\n|philosophy = [[Advaita Vedanta]]\n|honors     =  \n|footnotes  = \n}}\n{{Advaita}}\n{{Hindu philosophy}} \n'''Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da''' ([[Sanskrit]]: \u0917\u094c\u0921\u092a\u093e\u0926; fl. c. 6th century CE),{{sfn|Raju|1971|p=177}} also referred as '''{{IAST|Gau\u1e0dap\u0101d\u0101c\u0101rya}}''',{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}} was an early medieval era [[Hindu]] philosopher and scholar of the [[Vedanta]] school of [[Hindu philosophy]].{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}}<ref>TRV Murti (1955), The central philosophy of Buddhism, Routledge (2008 Reprint), {{ISBN|978-0-415-46118-4}}, page 114</ref> While details of his biography are uncertain, his ideas inspired others such as [[Adi Shankara]] who called him a ''Paramaguru'' (highest teacher).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}}{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|pp=125-126}}\n\nGaudapada was the author or compiler of the ''{{IAST|M\u0101\u1e47\u1e0dukya K\u0101rik\u0101}}'', also known as ''Gaudapada Karika''.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=308}} The text consists of four chapters (also called four books{{Sfn|Potter|1981|pp=106-111}}), of which Chapter<ref name=trvmurti114/>   Four uses Buddhist terminology thereby showing it was influenced by Buddhism. However, doctrinally Gaudapada's work is Vedantin, and not Buddhist.  {{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}}<ref name=trvmurti116/>{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=311}} The first three chapters of  Gaudapada's text have been influential in the [[Advaita Vedanta]] tradition.  Parts of the first chapter that include the ''[[Mandukya Upanishad]]'' have been considered a valid scriptural source by the [[Dvaita]] and [[Vishistadvaita]] schools of Vedanta.<ref name=trvmurti114/><ref name=iepgauda/>\n\n==Dates==\nThe century in which Gaudapada lived and his life details are uncertain.<ref name=iepgauda/> Estimates vary from early 6th{{sfn|Michael Comans|2000|p=163}}{{sfn|Raju|1971|p=177}} to 7th century CE.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=3}} He is generally dated from estimates for [[Adi Shankara]], whose teacher [[Govinda Bhagavatpada]] is presumed to be the direct disciple of Gaudapada. Shankara in some texts, refers to Gaudapada as the \"teacher's teacher\" who knows the tradition of the Ved\u0101nta (samprad\u0101ya-vit). Assuming how long each lived and when, Gaudapada is estimated to have lived sometime in the 7th century CE.{{sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}} Alternatively, states Potter, the phrase \"teacher's teacher\" should not be taken literally, and more in the sense of another phrase he uses for Gaudapada, namely ''Paramaguru'' (highest teacher).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}} He may have been the guru of Sankara's teacher, but was likely a more distant guru, states Michael Comans (aka [[Vasudevacharya]]).{{Sfn|Michael Comans|2000|p=2, 163}}\n\nAnother estimate places him around the early 6th century.<ref name=iepgauda>[http://www.iep.utm.edu/gau\u1e0dapad/ Gaudapada], Devanathan Jagannathan, University of Toronto, IEP</ref>{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|pp=125-126}} This estimate is based on Buddhist literature, and particularly those of scholars Bhavaviveka, Santaraksita and Kamalasila who cite ''Gau\u1e0dapada k\u0101rik\u0101s''.<ref name=iepgauda/>{{Sfn|Michael Comans|2000|pp=45-46}} Bhavaviveka was a contemporary of [[Dharmapala of Nalanda|Dharmapala]], states Karl Potter, while Chinese texts and travel accounts place Dharmapala in the mid 6th century CE.<ref name=iepgauda/> Assuming the Buddhist and Chinese records are reliable, and for Bhavaviveka to have quoted ''Gau\u1e0dapada k\u0101rik\u0101s'', Gaudapada must have lived around 500 CE, or sometime in the first half of 6th century CE. But, it is certain that Gaudapada lived after the 4th century because he cites some Buddhist views of N\u0101g\u0101rjuna and [[Asanga]], the latter of whom various accounts place in 4th century India.<ref name=iepgauda/>\n\n==Mandukya Karika==\n[[File:Gaudapada Mandukya Karika manuscript page sample i, Sanskrit, Devanagari script.jpg|thumb|left|The Mandukya Karika is an influential Vedanta text. Above: a manuscript page (Sanskrit, Devanagari script)]]\n\n===Authorship===\nGaudapada wrote or compiled{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=308}} the ''{{IAST|M\u0101\u1e47\u1e0dukya K\u0101rik\u0101}}'', also known as the ''{{IAST|Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da K\u0101rik\u0101}}'' and as the ''{{IAST|\u0100gama \u015a\u0101stra}}''.{{refn|group=note|Nakamura notes that there are contradictions in doctrine between the four chapters.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=308}}}} Some scholars, states Karl Potter, doubt that ''Gaudapada Karika'' was written by one author.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}}\n\nThe ''{{IAST|M\u0101\u1e47\u1e0dukya K\u0101rik\u0101}}'' is a concise explanation, in verse form,{{refn|group=note|Karika is defined by Monier-Williams as \"concise statement in verse of (esp. philosophy and grammar) doctrines\" in the Indian traditions.<ref>Monier Williams (1899), Sanskrit-English Dictionary, 2nd Ed, Oxford University Press, \u0915\u093e\u0930\u093f\u0915\u093e</ref>}} of the doctrines in ''[[Mandukya Upanishad]]'', one of the shortest but a profound [[Upanishad]], consisting of just 12 sentences.{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|p=126}} Even before the time of Adi Shankara, Mandukya Upanishad was considered to be a [[\u015aruti]], but not one particularly important during his era.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=280}} In later periods it acquired a higher value, and expressing the Upanishadic essence. {{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=280}} The Karika, notably, presents rational arguments from dream states, infinitude and finitude, space and time, causality, disintegration, and generation in support of the advaita doctrine.<ref>See Introduction of ''Mandukya Upanishad with the Karika of Gaudapada and the Commentary of Shankaracharya'' (trans.Swami Gambhirananda. Calcutta: Advaita Ashrama, 1995) and Domenic Marbaniang, \"The Advaitin Search for Unity in Diversity\", ''Epistemics of Divine Reality: An Argument for Rational Fideism'', PhD Dissertation (Bangalore: ACTS Academy of Higher Education, 2007).</ref>\n\nThe ''{{IAST|M\u0101\u1e47\u1e0dukya K\u0101rik\u0101}}'' is the earliest extant systematic treatise on {{IAST|Advaita Ved\u0101nta}},<ref>Sharma, C. (1997). ''A Critical Survey of Indian Philosophy'', Delhi: Motilal Banarsidass, {{ISBN|81-208-0365-5}}, p. 239</ref> though it is not the oldest work to present Advaita views,{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=211}} nor the only pre-Sankara work with the same type of teachings.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=211}} According to Hajime Nakamura, not only was the ''Gaudapada Karika'' treasured in the Advaita tradition, the text was revered and highly respected in [[Vishistadvaita]] and [[Dvaita]] Vedanta schools of Hinduism as well.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=280}} Gaudapada's text, adds Nakamura, was treasured but not considered a Sruti by Advaita scholars, while [[Ramanuja]] and [[Madhvacharya]] of non-Advaita schools considered its first chapter to be a Sruti.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=280}}\n\n===Contents===\nThe Gaudapadiya Karika has 215 [[Sanskrit prosody|metered verses]] which are divided into four chapters:<ref name=iepgauda/>\n# Chapter One (29 verses)&nbsp;\u2014 [[\u0100gama (Hinduism)|Agama, or Agama Prakarana]] (Traditional doctrine, includes 12 verses of the Mandukya Upanishad){{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}}{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|p=126}}\n# Chapter Two (38 verses)&nbsp;\u2014 Vaitathya Prakarana (Unreality){{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}}\n# Chapter Three (48 verses)&nbsp;\u2014 Adavaita Prakarana (Nonduality){{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}\n# Chapter Four (100 verses)&nbsp;\u2014 Alatasanti Prakarana (The Peace of the Firebrand){{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=110}}\n\nChronologically, according to [[Hajime Nakamura]], the Buddhist texts that quote from ''Gaudapada Karikas'' imply that the Vedantic ideas in the first three chapters are of greater antiquity. Most of Chapter Three of the compilation of ''Gaudapada Karika'' was complete by 400\u2013500 CE, states Nakamura.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=309}} He estimates that most of Chapter One was complete by 300\u2013400 CE, while Chapter Two which presupposes Chapter One can be dated to have been mostly complete after Chapter One but before Chapter Three.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=310}} Most of the Chapter Four was written sometime between 400 and 600 CE.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=309}}\n\n====Chapter One: Traditional Doctrine (Agama)====\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = '''Om is bliss'''\n<poem>\n[[Om]] is [[Brahman]],\nboth the higher and lower,\nas well as [[Ishvara]] residing in the hearts of everyone,\nit is both without measure and of unlimited measure,\nthe cessation of duality,\nit is bliss.\n</poem>\n |source = \u2014''Gaudapada Karika 1.28\u201329''<br />Translator: Karl Potter{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}}<ref name=karmarkar9>For Sanskrit original and an alternate translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n67/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 9 with footnotes, 66-67</ref>\n |bgcolor=#FFE0BB\n |align  = right\n}}\nThe [[\u0100tman (Hinduism)|Self]] resides in one's body in three forms: waking state, sleeping dreamy state and in deep sleep state, according to Potter's translation. When awake, the Self experiences the [[Vishva]] \u2013 the external objects and the visible; when dreaming, it experiences the [[Taijasa]] \u2013 the internal mind objects and what appears in the dreams; when in deep sleep, the Self experiences [[Praj\u00f1\u0101 (Hinduism)|Prajna]] \u2013 the unpolarized, the fruits of the heart and bliss.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}}<ref name=\"Sharma2012p41\"/> The description of these states of self are similar, states Arvind Sharma, to those found in [[Brihadaranyaka Upanishad]] and other ancient Hindu texts.<ref>{{cite book|author=Arvind Sharma|title=Sleep as a State of Consciousness in Advaita Vedanta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qVc5Deglvb8C |year=2012| publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-8430-2|pages=43\u201345}}</ref>\n\nGaudapada presents the competing traditional theories about life in vogue, before and in his times, in Karika 6 through 9. Some claim creation is the result of the expansion of the Self, some claim it is a mere magic show, some claim the creation is from God's desire, some claim ''Kala'' (time) creates all beings.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}} In Karika 10, the text states there is a fourth state of the Self, called Turiya, one of ''Advaita'' (nonduality), all pervading, unchanging and without ''Dukkha'' (sorrow).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}}<ref name=\"Sharma2012p41\">{{cite book|author=Arvind Sharma|title=Sleep as a State of Consciousness in Advaita Vedanta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qVc5Deglvb8C |year=2012| publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-8430-2|pages=41\u201348}}</ref> This fourth state of Self in ''Gaudapada Karika'' is found in chapters 8.7 through 8.12 of [[Chandogya Upanishad]], which discusses the \"four states of consciousness\" as awake, dream-filled sleep, deep sleep, and beyond deep sleep.<ref name=ptrajuchandogya>PT Raju (1985), Structural Depths of Indian Thought, State University New York Press, {{ISBN|978-0887061394}}, pages 32-33; '''Quote''': \"We can see that this story [in Chandogya Upanishad] is an anticipation of the Mandukya doctrine, (...)\"</ref><ref>Robert Hume, [https://archive.org/stream/thirteenprincipa028442mbp#page/n289/mode/2up Chandogya Upanishad - Eighth Prathapaka, Seventh through Twelfth Khanda], Oxford University Press, pages 268-273</ref>\n\nThe ''Vishva'' and ''Taijasa'' state of Self \u2013 states Gaudapada \u2013 can be a source of cause and effect, the ''Prajna'' is only cause, while ''Turiya'' state is neither.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}} It is the waking state and dream state that lead to awareness, errors and unawareness. The perceived duality of the world is [[Maya (illusion)|Maya]], when in reality there is only nonduality.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}} Chapter One ends with the discussion of the [[Om]] and its symbolism for Brahman, and the Atman within the heart of all living beings.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}}<ref name=karmarkar9/>{{Sfn|Isaeva|1995|p=30-34}}\n\n====Chapter Two: Unreality (Vaitathya)====\nUnreal are the dream objects during sleep, states Gaudapada, because the one who dreams never actually goes to place he dreams of, and because whatever situation he dreams about is something he leaves upon waking up. This is in the scripture [[Brihadaranyaka Upanishad]].{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}}\n\nIn the same sense, the true reality is covered up for man even in his waking state, state Karikas 4-6 of Chapter Two, because, translates Potter, \"any object nonexistent in the beginning and in the end is also nonexistent in the middle\".{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n67/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, page 10-11 with footnotes</ref>\n\nWhen we sleep, we feel the external things we dream about are real and the internal states as unreal, but in the awakened state we realize both are unreal. In the same way, in our waking state whatever we apprehend to be real and unreal are both unreal, covering up the true reality, state Karikas 10\u201315.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}} But this assertion leads to the obvious question, states Gaudapada, that if both internal and external are not true reality, who is it that imagines, who apprehends them and who cognizes?{{Sfn|Isaeva|1995|p=43}} Gaudapada submits his answer as the Atman (Self, soul).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}}{{Sfn|Isaeva|1995|p=43}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n69/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, page 12 with footnotes 11-12; Quote:<br /> \u0909\u092d\u092f\u094b\u0930\u092a\u093f \u0935\u0948\u0924\u0925\u094d\u092f\u0902 \u092d\u0947\u0926\u093e\u0928\u093e\u0902 \u0938\u094d\u0925\u093e\u0928\u092f\u094b\u0930\u094d\u092f\u0926\u093f \u0964<br />\u0915 \u090f\u0924\u093e\u0928\u094d\u092c\u0941\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0924\u0947 \u092d\u0947\u0926\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0915\u094b \u0935\u0948 \u0924\u0947\u0937\u093e\u0902 \u0935\u093f\u0915\u0932\u094d\u092a\u0915\u0903 \u0965 \u0967\u0967 \u0965<br />\u0915\u0932\u094d\u092a\u092f\u0924\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0924\u094d\u092e\u0928\u093e\u093d\u093d\u0924\u094d\u092e\u093e\u0928\u092e\u093e\u0924\u094d\u092e\u093e \u0926\u0947\u0935\u0903 \u0938\u094d\u0935\u092e\u093e\u092f\u092f\u093e |<br />\u0938 \u090f\u0935 \u092c\u0941\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0924\u0947 \u092d\u0947\u0926\u093e\u0928\u093f\u0924\u093f \u0935\u0947\u0926\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u0928\u093f\u0936\u094d\u091a\u092f\u0903 \u0965 \u0967\u0968 \u0965</ref>\n\n''Gaudapada Karika'' states that while we do grasp objects, we perceive, we think, but this does not connote the nature of reality and unreality, just like our fear of \"a rope for a serpent in darkness\".{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and an alternate translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n71/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, page 13-14 with footnotes</ref> We construct realities, states Gaudapada, and imagine ''Jivatman'' to be various things such as ''prana'' (brreath), ''loka'' (world), ''deva'' (gods), ''bhoktr'' (enjoyer), ''bhojya'' (enjoyables), ''sukshma'' (subtle), ''sthula'' (gross), ''murta'' (material), ''amurta'' (nonmaterial) and so on.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}<ref name=karmarkar16>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n73/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 15-17 with footnotes, 77-84</ref>{{Sfn|Isaeva|1995|pp=44-45}}\n\nWe imagine things in our mind, we create things in our mind, we destroy things in our mind, says Gaudapada; yet all these things are not different from It, the Atman (gender neutral).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}<ref name=karmarkar16/> All such constructions create dualities in our imagination, are [[Maya (illusion)|Maya]]. The true reality, state Karikas 33\u201336, is nondual and it is Atman.<ref name=karmarkar18/>{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}} Those who have mastered and grown past all attachments, past all fear and past all anger, they are past all dualities, know their Self, have secured the nonduality within. According to Karika 36\u201338, such wise individuals, do not care about praise from anyone, are beyond all rituals, are homeless wanderers, for they have realized the true inside them and outside; they, translates Potter, \"remain steadfastly true to nature\".{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}<ref name=karmarkar18>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n75/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 18-19 with footnotes, 85-88</ref>\n\n====Chapter Three: Nonduality (Advaita)====\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = '''Duties of worship'''\n<poem>\nDuties of worship arise only for those\nwho think something is born\nand who are thus miserable.\nI shall therefore speak of the\nnonmiserable state in which (...)\n</poem>\n |source = \u2014''Gaudapada Karika 3.1\u20132''<br />Translator: Karl Potter{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and an alternate translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n77/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 19-20 with footnotes 1 & 2 for Third Chapter</ref>\n |bgcolor=#FFE0BB\n |align  = right\n}}\nGaudapada opens this chapter by criticizing devotional worship of any form, and states that this assumes that the Brahman-Atman is born.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}<ref name=karmarkar19/> He states that the nondual Brahman-Atman (Self) can give rise to apparent duality (''Jivas'', individual souls), while remaining unaffected in the process. To this end he gives the analogy of space and jars.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|pp=108-109}} Self is like space and the Jivas are like space in jars. Just as space is enclosed in a jar, so is the Self manifested as Jivas. When the jar is destroyed the space in the jar merges into space so likewise, are the Jivas one of the Self.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|pp=108-109}}<ref name=karmarkar19>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n77/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 20-21 with footnotes</ref>\n\nGaudapada states that the Upanishads such as the ''Brihadaranyaka Upanishad'' teach this, that one's own Atman (self) is identical to the Atman in other beings, and all Atman are identical with the Brahman.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=109}} While some Upanishads, acknowledges Gaudapada, imply a difference between individual soul and the Brahman, those texts are discussing the apparent distinction (duality) when one believes in apparent creation. In reality, states Gaudapada, there is no creation of souls from Brahman as they are identical.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=109}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n79/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 21-23 with footnotes</ref> We must not confuse passages meant for spiritual instruction. According to Karikas 3.17-18, Gaudapada admits that dualists disagree with this view, but the ancient texts admit duality in the context of appearances, while \"nonduality is indeed the highest reality\", translates Karmarkar.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=109}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n81/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 23-24 with footnotes 17 & 18</ref>\n\nAccording to Karl Potter's translation of Karikas 3.33-36, an awareness that is without conceptual construction is unborn, and this is identical to the object of that awareness called [[Brahman]]. This awareness is not a metaphor, nor born, it is real. Such awareness shines forth without fear, beyond words and thought, is calm and unwavering, equanimous, and full of light.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=110}}<ref name=karmarkar27>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n85/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 27-29 with footnotes</ref> This inner contactless concentration (Asparsha yoga) is difficult for most including the [[yogis]], who see fear in what is fearlessly blissful.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=110}}{{Refn|group=note|Adi Shankara interprets this Karika somewhat differently, according to Comans.{{Sfn|Michael Comans|2000|p=166}}}} Such is the awareness that comes from self-reflection, understanding, giving up attachment to ''Dukkha'' (frustration) and ''Sukha'' (pleasure), where the mind rests in indescribable calmness within.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=110}}<ref name=karmarkar29>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n85/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 29-31 with footnotes</ref>{{Refn|group=note|\u0926\u0941\u0903\u0916\u0902 \u0938\u0930\u094d\u0935\u092e\u0928\u0941\u0938\u094d\u092e\u0943\u0924\u094d\u092f \u0915\u093e\u092e\u092d\u094b\u0917\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0928\u093f\u0935\u0930\u094d\u0924\u092f\u0947\u0924\u094d \u0964 \u0905\u091c\u0902 \u0938\u0930\u094d\u0935\u092e\u0928\u0941\u0938\u094d\u092e\u0943\u0924\u094d\u092f \u091c\u093e\u0924\u0902 \u0928\u0948\u0935 \u0924\u0941 \u092a\u0936\u094d\u092f\u0924\u093f \u0965 \u096a\u0969 \u0965(...)<br />\u0928\u093e\u093d\u093d\u0938\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0926\u092f\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0938\u0941\u0916\u0902 \u0924\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0928\u093f\u0903\u0938\u0919\u094d\u0917\u0903 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u091c\u094d\u091e\u092f\u093e \u092d\u0935\u0947\u0924\u094d \u0964 \u0928\u093f\u0936\u094d\u091a\u0932\u0902 \u0928\u093f\u0936\u094d\u091a\u0930\u091a\u094d\u091a\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0924\u092e\u0947\u0915\u0940\u0915\u0941\u0930\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0924\u094d\u092a\u094d\u0930\u092f\u0924\u094d\u0928\u0924\u0903 \u0965 \u096a\u096b \u0965(...)<br />\u0938\u094d\u0935\u0938\u094d\u0925\u0902 \u0936\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u0902 \u0938\u0928\u093f\u0930\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0923\u092e\u0915\u0925\u094d\u092f\u0902 \u0938\u0941\u0916\u092e\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0924\u092e\u092e\u094d \u0964 \u0905\u091c\u092e\u091c\u0947\u0928 \u091c\u094d\u091e\u0947\u092f\u0947\u0928 \u0938\u0930\u094d\u0935\u091c\u094d\u091e\u0902 \u092a\u0930\u093f\u091a\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0924\u0947 \u0965 \u096a\u096d \u0965<ref name=karmarkar29/>}}\n\n====Chapter Four: The Peace of The Firebrand (Alatasanti)====\nThe last chapter of ''Gaudapada Karika'' has a different style than the first three, and it opens by expressing reverence for all \"the greatest of men\", who are like the cosmic space through their awareness of nonduality, free from self-contradictions and confusion, and who understand [[Dharma]].{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=110}} Karikas 3\u201310 repeat some content from previous chapters, but with some word substitutions.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=111}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n89/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 32-33 with footnotes</ref> Karikas 11\u201313 quote the key duality premise of [[Samkhya]] school of Hindu philosophy, cross examines it, then asks how and why is cause eternal? The text states that the Samkhya premise \"cause is born as its effect\" leads to infinite regress, which is not persuasive.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=111}}\n\n''Gaudapada Karika'' then acknowledges the theory of [[Ajativada]] or non-origination of the ''Buddhas'' (Buddhists).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=111}} Like Samkhya premise, the text praises and cross examines it, in three ways: first, non-origination premises makes sense when neither the point of origin nor the end of something is known, but we know the point of origin of any example of something produced and there ''Ajativada'' premise does not follow; secondly, the ''Ajativada'' premise commits the ''Sadhyasama'' fallacy of reasoning by offering examples of what is yet to be proved.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=111}} Thirdly, state Karikas 29\u201341, neither [[samsara]] nor [[moksha|mukti]] has a beginning or end, because if something is born it must have an end, and something that is unborn has no end.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=112}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n97/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 39-41 with footnotes</ref>\n\nKarikas 45\u201352 state that  only (''Vijnana'') consciousness is real, explaining it with an example of fire stick before and during the time it burns, and adding we construct and deconstruct our state of awareness.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=112}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n101/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 43-44 with footnotes</ref> Karikas 53\u201356 assert that there is no causation, no effects, and repeats that consciousness is the only one real thing.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|pp=112-113}} Everything is [[impermanence|impermanent]], nothing is eternal and everything is also without origination by nature, state Karikas 57\u201360.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=113}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n103/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 45-46 with footnotes</ref>\n\nKarikas 61\u201381 repeat text on four states from earlier chapters to re-emphasize the premises about impermanence and non-origination.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=113}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n105/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 47-52 with footnotes</ref> Attachment to unreality causes desire, sorrow (Dukkha) and fear, while detachment leads to freeing from such states and to ''samadhi''.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=113}} There are three stages of understanding state Karikas 87\u201389: ''Laukika'' (ordinary. which cognizes object and subject as real), ''Shuddha laukika'' (purified ordinary, perceiving is considered real but not the objects) and ''Lokottara'' (supramundane, where neither objects nor perceiving are cognized as real).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=113}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n111/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 53-54 with footnotes</ref>\n\nKarikas 90\u2013100 presents ''Agrayana'' (vehicle) to knowing. The text states, \"all dharmas are without beginning, without variety, and are consciousness only\".{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=113}} Duality is for the unwise, nonduality and undifferentiated Reality is for the wise and difficult to grasp. The last ''Karikas'' of the Chapter Four add, translates Karl Potter, \"this the ''Buddhas'' understand, the Buddha instructs us that consciousness does not reach the dharmas, yet the Buddha said nothing about either consciousness or dharmas!\"{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=114}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n113/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 55-56 with footnotes</ref>\n\n===Relationship to Buddhism===\nThe influence of Buddhist doctrines on Gaudapada has been a vexed question.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}}{{Sfn|Michael Comans|2000|p=2}}\n\nOne school of scholars, such as Bhattacharya and Raju, state that Gaudapada took over the Buddhist doctrines that [[Yogacara#Representation-only|ultimate reality is pure consciousness (''vij\u00f1apti-m\u0101tra'')]]{{sfn|Raju|1971|p=177}}{{refn|group=note|It is often used interchangeably with the term ''citta-m\u0101tra'', but they have different meanings. The standard translation of both terms is \"consciousness-only\" or \"mind-only.\" Several modern researchers object this translation, and the accompanying label of \"absolute idealism\" or \"idealistic monism\".{{sfn|Kochumuttom|1999|p=1}} A better translation for ''vij\u00f1apti-m\u0101tra'' is ''representation-only''.{{sfn|Kochumuttom|1999|p=5}}}} and \"that the nature of the world is the four-cornered negation, which is the structure of M\u0101y\u0101\".{{sfn|Raju|1971|p=177}}{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|pp=126, 143-144}}{{refn|group=note|1. Something is. 2. It is not. 3. It both is and is not. 4. It neither is nor is not.{{sfn|Garfield|Priest|2003}}{{page needed|date=August 2016}} The 'four-cornered negation' is an English gloss of the Sanskrit, [[Catu\u1e63ko\u1e6di|Chatushkoti]].{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}}} Gaudapada \"wove [both doctrines] into the philosophy of ''Mandukaya Upanisad'', which was further developed by Shankara\".{{sfn|Raju|1971|p=177-178}}{{refn|group=note|The influence of [[Mahayana Buddhism]] on other religions and philosophies was not limited to Vedanta. Kalupahana notes that the [[Visuddhimagga]] \u2013 a Theravada Buddhist tradition, contains \"some metaphysical speculations, such as those of the Sarvastivadins, the Sautrantikas, and even the [[Yogacara|Yogacarins]]\".{{sfn|Kalupahana|1994|p=206}}}}\n\nOf particular interest is Chapter Four, in which according to Bhattacharya, two karikas refer to the [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] and the term ''Asparsayoga'' is borrowed from Buddhism.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}} According to Murti, \"the conclusion is irresistible that Gaudapada, a Vedanta philosopher, is attempting an advaitic interpretation of Vedanta in the light of the Madhyamika and Yogcara doctrines. He even freely quotes and appeals to them.\"<ref name=trvmurti114>TRV Murti (1955), The central philosophy of Buddhism, Routledge (2008 Reprint), {{ISBN|978-0-415-46118-4}}, pages 114-115</ref> However, adds Murti, the doctrines are unlike Buddhism. Chapter One, Two and Three are entirely Vedantin and founded on the Upanishads, with little Buddhist flavor.<ref name=trvmurti114/> While the first three chapters discuss [[Brahman]] and Atman (soul, Self), Chapter Four doesn't. This, according to Murti,<ref name=trvmurti114/> may be because this was authored by someone else and not Gaudapada, a position shared by Richard King.<ref name=iepgauda/> Further, state both Murti and King, no Vedanta scholars who followed Gaudapada ever quoted from Chapter Four, they only quote from the first three.<ref name=trvmurti114/><ref name=iepgauda/> According to Sarma, Chapter Four may well have been written by Gaudapada assuming he was fully conversant with Mahayana school's teachings, yet \"to mistake him to be a hidden or open Buddhist is absurd\".{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|pp=145-147}} The doctrines of Gaudapada and Buddhism are totally opposed, states Murti:<ref name=trvmurti114/>\n\n{{Quote|\nWe have been talking of borrowing, influence and relationship in rather general terms. It is necessary to define the possible nature of the borrowing, granting that it did take place. (...) The Vedantins stake everything on the [[Atman (Hinduism)|Atman]] (Brahman) and accept the authority of the Upanishads. We have pointed out at length the [[Anatta|Nairatmya]] standpoint of Buddhism and its total opposition to the Atman (soul, substance, the permanent and universal) in any form.\n|TRV Murti|''The Central Philosophy of Buddhism''<ref name=trvmurti116>TRV Murti (1955), The central philosophy of Buddhism, Routledge (2008 Reprint), {{ISBN|978-0-415-46118-4}}, page 116</ref>}}\n\nAdvaitins particularly have traditionally challenged the Buddhist influence thesis.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}} Modern scholarship generally accepts that Gaudapada was influenced by Buddhism, at least in terms of using Buddhist terminology to explain his ideas, but adds that Gaudapada was a Vedantin and not a Buddhist.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}}\n\n==Other works by Gaudapadacharya==\nA number of additional works are attributed to Gaudapada, but their authenticity is uncertain.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=104}} The attributed works are:{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=104}}{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=311}}\n* A [[bhasya]] on ''[[Brihadaranyaka Upanishad]]''\n* A bhasya on ''[[Nrisimha Tapaniya Upanishad]]''\n* A bhasya on [[Anugita]]\n* ''Durga Saptashati Tika''&nbsp;\u2014 A bhasya on [[Devi Mahatmya]]\n* ''Sri Vidyaratna Sutra'' bhasya\n* ''Subhagodaya on Sri Vidya''\n* ''Uttara Gita Bhashya''\n\nGaudapada is also credited with a commentary on ''Samkhyakarikas''. According to Potter, the naive nature of this commentary is in sharp contrast to the depth of reflection in ''Gaudapada Karikas'', and the commentary on ''Samkhyakarikas'' is unlikely to be one by Gaudapada.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=104}}\n\n==Advaita guru-parampar\u0101==\n{{Main|Advaita Guru Parampar\u0101}}\n\nGaudapada is one of the key persons in the Advaita Vedanta.{{Sfn|Michael Comans|2000|p=2}} He is traditionally said to have been highly influential on [[Adi Shankara]],{{sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}} one of the most important figures in Vedic philosophy.\n\n==Shri Gaudapadacharya Math==\n{{Main|Shri Gaudapadacharya Math}}\n\nShri Gaudapadacharya Math{{refn|group=note|{{lang-sa|\u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0938\u0902\u0938\u094d\u0925\u093e\u0928 \u0917\u094c\u0921\u092a\u0926\u093e\u091a\u093e\u0930\u094d\u092f \u092e\u0920}}, {{IAST|\u015ar\u012b Sansth\u0101na Gau\u1e0dapad\u0101c\u0101rya Ma\u1e6dha}}}}, also known as '''{{IAST|Kava\u1e37\u0113 ma\u1e6dha}}''' {{lang|skt|\u0915\u0935\u0933\u0947 \u092e\u0920}}, is the oldest [[matha]] of the [[South India]]n [[Saraswat Brahmin]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Shri Gowdapadacharya & Shri Kavale Math (A Commemoration volume)| page=10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shrikavalemath.org.in/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=25 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225124923/http://shrikavalemath.org.in/ |archive-date=25 December 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Peetadhipathi]] \"head monk\" is \u015ar\u012b Gau\u1e0dapad\u0101c\u0101rya. [[Rajapur Saraswat Brahmins]] and [[Smartism|Smartist]] [[Goud Saraswat Brahmin]]s are its main disciples.<ref>http://www.shrikavalemath.org.in/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225124923/http://shrikavalemath.org.in/ |date=25 December 2018 }}, Title: About Kavale matha.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n'''List of Math'''\n*[[Kashi Math]]\n*[[Gokarna Math]]\n*[[Chitrapur Math]]\n*[[Dvaita]]\n*[[Madhwacharya]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Published sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | last =Bhatta | first =Rathnakara | year =2013 | title =Shree Shankarayana (May. 2013), pp. 190\u2013380. | url =http://www.goodreads.com/author_blog_posts/4295191-shree-shankarayana}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|author=Michael Comans|title=The Method of Early Advaita Ved\u0101nta: A Study of Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da, \u015aa\u1e45kara, Sure\u015bvara, and Padmap\u0101da|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sx12hxoFVqwC|year=2000|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-1722-7}}\n* {{Citation | last1 =Garfield | first1 =Jay L. | last2 =Priest | first2 =Graham | year =2003 | title =Nagarjuna and the Limits of Thought, Philosophy East & West Volume 53, Number 1 January 2003 1\u201321 | url =http://www.thezensite.com/ZenEssays/Nagarjuna/NagarjunaTheLimitsOfThought.pdf}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Isaeva|first=Natalia V. |title=From Early Vedanta to Kashmir Shaivism: Gaudapada, Bhartrhari, and Abhinavagupta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hMCFQ39cHNkC |year=1995|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-2449-0}}\n* {{Citation | last =Kalupahana | first =David J. | year =1994 | title =A History of Buddhist Philosophy | place =Delhi | publisher =Motilal Banarsidass Publishers Private Limited}}\n* {{Citation | last =Kochumuttom | first =Thomas A. | year =1999 | title =A Buddhist Doctrine of Experience. A New Translation and Interpretation of the Works of Vasubandhu the Yogacarin | place =Delhi | publisher =Motilal Banarsidass}}\n* {{Citation | last =Nakamura | first =Hajime | year =2004 | title =A History of Early Vedanta Philosophy. Part Two | place =Delhi | publisher =Motilal Banarsidass Publishers Private Limited}}\n*{{cite book |author=Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da \u0100c\u0101rya |author2=\u015aa\u1e45kar\u0101c\u0101rya |author3=Nikhilananda, Swami |author4= V Subrahmanya Iyer  |year=1990 |title=M\u0101\u1e47\u1e0d\u016bkyopani\u1e63ad : with Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da's K\u0101rik\u0101 and Sa\u1e45kara's commentary |publisher=Advaita Ashrama |location=Calcutta |isbn=81-7505-022-5 |pages= }}\n* {{Citation | last =Potter | first =Karl. H. | year =1981 | title =''Gaudapada,'' Encyclopedia of Indian Philosophies: Advaita Ved\u0101nta up to \u015aa\u1e43kara and his pupils, Volume 3, ''pp. 103-114'' | place =Delhi | publisher = Motilal Banarsidass | isbn =81-208-0310-8}}\n* {{Citation | last =Raju | first =P.T. | year =1971 | title =The Philosophical Traditions of India | place =Delhi | publisher =Motilal Banarsidass (1992 Reprint)}}\n* {{Citation | last =Sarma | first =Chandradhar | year =2007 |isbn= 978-8120813120 | title =The Advaita Tradition in Indian Philosophy | publisher =Motilal Banarsidass}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | last =Dvivedi | first =Manilal N. | author-link=Manilal Dwivedi | year =2003 | title =The Mandukyopanishad: With Gaudapada's Karikas and the Bhashya of Sankara | publisher =Jain Publishing Company}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fox|first=Douglas|title=Dispelling the Illusion|location=Albany|publisher=SUNY Press|year=1993}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jones|first=Richard H.|title=Gaudapada: Advaita Vedanta's First Philosopher|location=New York|publisher=Jackson Square Books|year=2014}}\n* {{cite book | last =King | first =Richard | year =1995  | title =Early Advaita Vedanta and Buddhism: The Mahayana Context of the Gaudapadiya-Karika | publisher =SUNY Press}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author}}  \n* [https://www.wisdomlib.org/hinduism/book/mandukya-upanishad-karika-bhashya/index.html The Mandukya Upanishad/Karika, Shankara\u2019s Commentary and Anandagiri\u2019s Tika] Translated by Swami Nikhilananda, online ebook\n* [http://www.universaltheosophy.com/pdf-library/Mandukya%20Upanishad%20with%20Gaudapada-Karika_Johnston.pdf Gaudapada Karika], Translation and commentary by Charles Johnston, Theosophical Quarterly\n* [http://www.advaita-vedanta.org/avhp/gaudapada.html advaita-vedanta.org, ''Gaudapada'']\n* [http://www.swamij.com/upanishad-mandukya-karika.htm Mandukya Upanishad with Gaudapada's Karika]\n* [http://www.advaitayoga.org/advaitayogaarticles/karika.html P.J. Mazumdar, ''Gaudapada's Karika on the Mandukya Upanishad'']\n\n{{Hindudharma}}\n{{Indian Philosophy}}\n{{philosophy of religion}} \n{{Portal bar|Hinduism|India|Religion}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaudapada}}\n[[Category:6th-century Indian philosophers]]\n[[Category:6th-century Indian monks]]\n[[Category:Ascetics]]\n[[Category:Advaitin philosophers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Indian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Indian writers]]\n[[Category:Consequentialists]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophers]]\n[[Category:Hindu reformers]]\n[[Category:Hindu scholars]]\n[[Category:Idealists]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu monks]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu missionaries]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Indian yogis]]\n[[Category:Medieval Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Vedanta]]\n[[Category:Ontologists]]\n[[Category:Pantheists]]\n[[Category:Sanskrit writers]]\n[[Category:Indian male writers]]\n[[Category:6th-century Indian writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}} \n{{Infobox Hindu leader\n|name       = Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da\n|image      = Shri Gaudapadacharya Statue.jpg\n|caption    = Adi Guru Shri Gau\u1e0dap\u0101d\u0101ch\u0101rya\n|birth_date =\n|birth_place=   \n|birth_name =\n|death_date =\n|death_place= \n|known       =\n|religion   = [[Hinduism]] \n|founder    = [[Shri Gaudapadacharya Math]]\n|philosophy = [[Advaita Vedanta]]\n|honors     =  \n|footnotes  = \n}}\n{{Advaita}}\n{{Hindu philosophy}} \n'''Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da''' ([[Sanskrit]]: \u0917\u094c\u0921\u092a\u093e\u0926; fl. c. 6th century CE),{{sfn|Raju|1971|p=177}} also referred as '''{{IAST|Gau\u1e0dap\u0101d\u0101c\u0101rya}}''',{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}} was an early medieval era [[Hindu]] philosopher and scholar of the [[Vedanta]] school of [[Hindu philosophy]].{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}}<ref>TRV Murti (1955), The central philosophy of Buddhism, Routledge (2008 Reprint), {{ISBN|978-0-415-46118-4}}, page 114</ref> While details of his biography are uncertain, his ideas inspired others such as [[Adi Shankara]] who called him a ''Paramaguru'' (highest teacher).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}}{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|pp=125-126}}\n\nGaudapada was the author or compiler of the ''{{IAST|M\u0101\u1e47\u1e0dukya K\u0101rik\u0101}}'', also known as ''Gaudapada Karika''.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=308}} The text consists of four chapters (also called four books{{Sfn|Potter|1981|pp=106-111}}), of which Chapter<ref name=trvmurti114/>   Four uses Buddhist terminology thereby showing it was influenced by Buddhism. However, doctrinally Gaudapada's work is Vedantin, and not Buddhist.  {{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}}<ref name=trvmurti116/>{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=311}} The first three chapters of  Gaudapada's text have been influential in the [[Advaita Vedanta]] tradition.  Parts of the first chapter that include the ''[[Mandukya Upanishad]]'' have been considered a valid scriptural source by the [[Dvaita]] and [[Vishistadvaita]] schools of Vedanta.<ref name=trvmurti114/><ref name=iepgauda/>\n\n==Dates==\nThe century in which Gaudapada lived and his life details are uncertain.<ref name=iepgauda/> Estimates vary from early 6th{{sfn|Michael Comans|2000|p=163}}{{sfn|Raju|1971|p=177}} to 7th century CE.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=3}} He is generally dated from estimates for [[Adi Shankara]], whose teacher [[Govinda Bhagavatpada]] is presumed to be the direct disciple of Gaudapada. Shankara in some texts, refers to Gaudapada as the \"teacher's teacher\" who knows the tradition of the Ved\u0101nta (samprad\u0101ya-vit). Assuming how long each lived and when, Gaudapada is estimated to have lived sometime in the 7th century CE.{{sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}} Alternatively, states Potter, the phrase \"teacher's teacher\" should not be taken literally, and more in the sense of another phrase he uses for Gaudapada, namely ''Paramaguru'' (highest teacher).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}} He may have been the guru of Sankara's teacher, but was likely a more distant guru, states Michael Comans (aka [[Vasudevacharya]]).{{Sfn|Michael Comans|2000|p=2, 163}}\n\nAnother estimate places him around the early 6th century.<ref name=iepgauda>[http://www.iep.utm.edu/gau\u1e0dapad/ Gaudapada], Devanathan Jagannathan, University of Toronto, IEP</ref>{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|pp=125-126}} This estimate is based on Buddhist literature, and particularly those of scholars Bhavaviveka, Santaraksita and Kamalasila who cite ''Gau\u1e0dapada k\u0101rik\u0101s''.<ref name=iepgauda/>{{Sfn|Michael Comans|2000|pp=45-46}} Bhavaviveka was a contemporary of [[Dharmapala of Nalanda|Dharmapala]], states Karl Potter, while Chinese texts and travel accounts place Dharmapala in the mid 6th century CE.<ref name=iepgauda/> Assuming the Buddhist and Chinese records are reliable, and for Bhavaviveka to have quoted ''Gau\u1e0dapada k\u0101rik\u0101s'', Gaudapada must have lived around 500 CE, or sometime in the first half of 6th century CE. But, it is certain that Gaudapada lived after the 4th century because he cites some Buddhist views of N\u0101g\u0101rjuna and [[Asanga]], the latter of whom various accounts place in 4th century India.<ref name=iepgauda/>\n\n==Mandukya Karika==\n[[File:Gaudapada Mandukya Karika manuscript page sample i, Sanskrit, Devanagari script.jpg|thumb|left|The Mandukya Karika is an influential Vedanta text. Above: a manuscript page (Sanskrit, Devanagari script)]]\n\n===Authorship===\nGaudapada wrote or compiled{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=308}} the ''{{IAST|M\u0101\u1e47\u1e0dukya K\u0101rik\u0101}}'', also known as the ''{{IAST|Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da K\u0101rik\u0101}}'' and as the ''{{IAST|\u0100gama \u015a\u0101stra}}''.{{refn|group=note|Nakamura notes that there are contradictions in doctrine between the four chapters.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=308}}}} Some scholars, states Karl Potter, doubt that ''Gaudapada Karika'' was written by one author.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}}\n\nThe ''{{IAST|M\u0101\u1e47\u1e0dukya K\u0101rik\u0101}}'' is a concise explanation, in verse form,{{refn|group=note|Karika is defined by Monier-Williams as \"concise statement in verse of (esp. philosophy and grammar) doctrines\" in the Indian traditions.<ref>Monier Williams (1899), Sanskrit-English Dictionary, 2nd Ed, Oxford University Press, \u0915\u093e\u0930\u093f\u0915\u093e</ref>}} of the doctrines in ''[[Mandukya Upanishad]]'', one of the shortest but a profound [[Upanishad]], consisting of just 12 sentences.{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|p=126}} Even before the time of Adi Shankara, Mandukya Upanishad was considered to be a [[\u015aruti]], but not one particularly important during his era.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=280}} In later periods it acquired a higher value, and expressing the Upanishadic essence. {{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=280}} The Karika, notably, presents rational arguments from dream states, infinitude and finitude, space and time, causality, disintegration, and generation in support of the advaita doctrine.<ref>See Introduction of ''Mandukya Upanishad with the Karika of Gaudapada and the Commentary of Shankaracharya'' (trans.Swami Gambhirananda. Calcutta: Advaita Ashrama, 1995) and Domenic Marbaniang, \"The Advaitin Search for Unity in Diversity\", ''Epistemics of Divine Reality: An Argument for Rational Fideism'', PhD Dissertation (Bangalore: ACTS Academy of Higher Education, 2007).</ref>\n\nThe ''{{IAST|M\u0101\u1e47\u1e0dukya K\u0101rik\u0101}}'' is the earliest extant systematic treatise on {{IAST|Advaita Ved\u0101nta}},<ref>Sharma, C. (1997). ''A Critical Survey of Indian Philosophy'', Delhi: Motilal Banarsidass, {{ISBN|81-208-0365-5}}, p. 239</ref> though it is not the oldest work to present Advaita views,{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=211}} nor the only pre-Sankara work with the same type of teachings.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=211}} According to Hajime Nakamura, not only was the ''Gaudapada Karika'' treasured in the Advaita tradition, the text was revered and highly respected in [[Vishistadvaita]] and [[Dvaita]] Vedanta schools of Hinduism as well.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=280}} Gaudapada's text, adds Nakamura, was treasured but not considered a Sruti by Advaita scholars, while [[Ramanuja]] and [[Madhvacharya]] of non-Advaita schools considered its first chapter to be a Sruti.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=280}}\n\n===Contents===\nThe Gaudapadiya Karika has 215 [[Sanskrit prosody|metered verses]] which are divided into four chapters:<ref name=iepgauda/>\n# Chapter One (29 verses)&nbsp;\u2014 [[\u0100gama (Hinduism)|Agama, or Agama Prakarana]] (Traditional doctrine, includes 12 verses of the Mandukya Upanishad){{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}}{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|p=126}}\n# Chapter Two (38 verses)&nbsp;\u2014 Vaitathya Prakarana (Unreality){{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}}\n# Chapter Three (48 verses)&nbsp;\u2014 Adavaita Prakarana (Nonduality){{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}\n# Chapter Four (100 verses)&nbsp;\u2014 Alatasanti Prakarana (The Peace of the Firebrand){{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=110}}\n\nChronologically, according to [[Hajime Nakamura]], the Buddhist texts that quote from ''Gaudapada Karikas'' imply that the Vedantic ideas in the first three chapters are of greater antiquity. Most of Chapter Three of the compilation of ''Gaudapada Karika'' was complete by 400\u2013500 CE, states Nakamura.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=309}} He estimates that most of Chapter One was complete by 300\u2013400 CE, while Chapter Two which presupposes Chapter One can be dated to have been mostly complete after Chapter One but before Chapter Three.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=310}} Most of the Chapter Four was written sometime between 400 and 600 CE.{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=309}}\n\n====Chapter One: Traditional Doctrine (Agama)====\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = '''Om is bliss'''\n<poem>\n[[Om]] is [[Brahman]],\nboth the higher and lower,\nas well as [[Ishvara]] residing in the hearts of everyone,\nit is both without measure and of unlimited measure,\nthe cessation of duality,\nit is bliss.\n</poem>\n |source = \u2014''Gaudapada Karika 1.28\u201329''<br />Translator: Karl Potter{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}}<ref name=karmarkar9>For Sanskrit original and an alternate translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n67/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 9 with footnotes, 66-67</ref>\n |bgcolor=#FFE0BB\n |align  = right\n}}\nThe [[\u0100tman (Hinduism)|Self]] resides in one's body in three forms: waking state, sleeping dreamy state and in deep sleep state, according to Potter's translation. When awake, the Self experiences the [[Vishva]] \u2013 the external objects and the visible; when dreaming, it experiences the [[Taijasa]] \u2013 the internal mind objects and what appears in the dreams; when in deep sleep, the Self experiences [[Praj\u00f1\u0101 (Hinduism)|Prajna]] \u2013 the unpolarized, the fruits of the heart and bliss.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}}<ref name=\"Sharma2012p41\"/> The description of these states of self are similar, states Arvind Sharma, to those found in [[Brihadaranyaka Upanishad]] and other ancient Hindu texts.<ref>{{cite book|author=Arvind Sharma|title=Sleep as a State of Consciousness in Advaita Vedanta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qVc5Deglvb8C |year=2012| publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-8430-2|pages=43\u201345}}</ref>\n\nGaudapada presents the competing traditional theories about life in vogue, before and in his times, in Karika 6 through 9. Some claim creation is the result of the expansion of the Self, some claim it is a mere magic show, some claim the creation is from God's desire, some claim ''Kala'' (time) creates all beings.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}} In Karika 10, the text states there is a fourth state of the Self, called Turiya, one of ''Advaita'' (nonduality), all pervading, unchanging and without ''Dukkha'' (sorrow).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}}<ref name=\"Sharma2012p41\">{{cite book|author=Arvind Sharma|title=Sleep as a State of Consciousness in Advaita Vedanta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qVc5Deglvb8C |year=2012| publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-8430-2|pages=41\u201348}}</ref> This fourth state of Self in ''Gaudapada Karika'' is found in chapters 8.7 through 8.12 of [[Chandogya Upanishad]], which discusses the \"four states of consciousness\" as awake, dream-filled sleep, deep sleep, and beyond deep sleep.<ref name=ptrajuchandogya>PT Raju (1985), Structural Depths of Indian Thought, State University New York Press, {{ISBN|978-0887061394}}, pages 32-33; '''Quote''': \"We can see that this story [in Chandogya Upanishad] is an anticipation of the Mandukya doctrine, (...)\"</ref><ref>Robert Hume, [https://archive.org/stream/thirteenprincipa028442mbp#page/n289/mode/2up Chandogya Upanishad - Eighth Prathapaka, Seventh through Twelfth Khanda], Oxford University Press, pages 268-273</ref>\n\nThe ''Vishva'' and ''Taijasa'' state of Self \u2013 states Gaudapada \u2013 can be a source of cause and effect, the ''Prajna'' is only cause, while ''Turiya'' state is neither.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}} It is the waking state and dream state that lead to awareness, errors and unawareness. The perceived duality of the world is [[Maya (illusion)|Maya]], when in reality there is only nonduality.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}} Chapter One ends with the discussion of the [[Om]] and its symbolism for Brahman, and the Atman within the heart of all living beings.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=106}}<ref name=karmarkar9/>{{Sfn|Isaeva|1995|p=30-34}}\n\n====Chapter Two: Unreality (Vaitathya)====\nUnreal are the dream objects during sleep, states Gaudapada, because the one who dreams never actually goes to place he dreams of, and because whatever situation he dreams about is something he leaves upon waking up. This is in the scripture [[Brihadaranyaka Upanishad]].{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}}\n\nIn the same sense, the true reality is covered up for man even in his waking state, state Karikas 4-6 of Chapter Two, because, translates Potter, \"any object nonexistent in the beginning and in the end is also nonexistent in the middle\".{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n67/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, page 10-11 with footnotes</ref>\n\nWhen we sleep, we feel the external things we dream about are real and the internal states as unreal, but in the awakened state we realize both are unreal. In the same way, in our waking state whatever we apprehend to be real and unreal are both unreal, covering up the true reality, state Karikas 10\u201315.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}} But this assertion leads to the obvious question, states Gaudapada, that if both internal and external are not true reality, who is it that imagines, who apprehends them and who cognizes?{{Sfn|Isaeva|1995|p=43}} Gaudapada submits his answer as the Atman (Self, soul).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}}{{Sfn|Isaeva|1995|p=43}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n69/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, page 12 with footnotes 11-12; Quote:<br /> \u0909\u092d\u092f\u094b\u0930\u092a\u093f \u0935\u0948\u0924\u0925\u094d\u092f\u0902 \u092d\u0947\u0926\u093e\u0928\u093e\u0902 \u0938\u094d\u0925\u093e\u0928\u092f\u094b\u0930\u094d\u092f\u0926\u093f \u0964<br />\u0915 \u090f\u0924\u093e\u0928\u094d\u092c\u0941\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0924\u0947 \u092d\u0947\u0926\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0915\u094b \u0935\u0948 \u0924\u0947\u0937\u093e\u0902 \u0935\u093f\u0915\u0932\u094d\u092a\u0915\u0903 \u0965 \u0967\u0967 \u0965<br />\u0915\u0932\u094d\u092a\u092f\u0924\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0924\u094d\u092e\u0928\u093e\u093d\u093d\u0924\u094d\u092e\u093e\u0928\u092e\u093e\u0924\u094d\u092e\u093e \u0926\u0947\u0935\u0903 \u0938\u094d\u0935\u092e\u093e\u092f\u092f\u093e |<br />\u0938 \u090f\u0935 \u092c\u0941\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0924\u0947 \u092d\u0947\u0926\u093e\u0928\u093f\u0924\u093f \u0935\u0947\u0926\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u0928\u093f\u0936\u094d\u091a\u092f\u0903 \u0965 \u0967\u0968 \u0965</ref>\n\n''Gaudapada Karika'' states that while we do grasp objects, we perceive, we think, but this does not connote the nature of reality and unreality, just like our fear of \"a rope for a serpent in darkness\".{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=107}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and an alternate translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n71/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, page 13-14 with footnotes</ref> We construct realities, states Gaudapada, and imagine ''Jivatman'' to be various things such as ''prana'' (brreath), ''loka'' (world), ''deva'' (gods), ''bhoktr'' (enjoyer), ''bhojya'' (enjoyables), ''sukshma'' (subtle), ''sthula'' (gross), ''murta'' (material), ''amurta'' (nonmaterial) and so on.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}<ref name=karmarkar16>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n73/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 15-17 with footnotes, 77-84</ref>{{Sfn|Isaeva|1995|pp=44-45}}\n\nWe imagine things in our mind, we create things in our mind, we destroy things in our mind, says Gaudapada; yet all these things are not different from It, the Atman (gender neutral).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}<ref name=karmarkar16/> All such constructions create dualities in our imagination, are [[Maya (illusion)|Maya]]. The true reality, state Karikas 33\u201336, is nondual and it is Atman.<ref name=karmarkar18/>{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}} Those who have mastered and grown past all attachments, past all fear and past all anger, they are past all dualities, know their Self, have secured the nonduality within. According to Karika 36\u201338, such wise individuals, do not care about praise from anyone, are beyond all rituals, are homeless wanderers, for they have realized the true inside them and outside; they, translates Potter, \"remain steadfastly true to nature\".{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}<ref name=karmarkar18>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n75/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 18-19 with footnotes, 85-88</ref>\n\n====Chapter Three: Nonduality (Advaita)====\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = '''Duties of worship'''\n<poem>\nDuties of worship arise only for those\nwho think something is born\nand who are thus miserable.\nI shall therefore speak of the\nnonmiserable state in which (...)\n</poem>\n |source = \u2014''Gaudapada Karika 3.1\u20132''<br />Translator: Karl Potter{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and an alternate translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n77/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 19-20 with footnotes 1 & 2 for Third Chapter</ref>\n |bgcolor=#FFE0BB\n |align  = right\n}}\nGaudapada opens this chapter by criticizing devotional worship of any form, and states that this assumes that the Brahman-Atman is born.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=108}}<ref name=karmarkar19/> He states that the nondual Brahman-Atman (Self) can give rise to apparent duality (''Jivas'', individual souls), while remaining unaffected in the process. To this end he gives the analogy of space and jars.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|pp=108-109}} Self is like space and the Jivas are like space in jars. Just as space is enclosed in a jar, so is the Self manifested as Jivas. When the jar is destroyed the space in the jar merges into space so likewise, are the Jivas one of the Self.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|pp=108-109}}<ref name=karmarkar19>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n77/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 20-21 with footnotes</ref>\n\nGaudapada states that the Upanishads such as the ''Brihadaranyaka Upanishad'' teach this, that one's own Atman (self) is identical to the Atman in other beings, and all Atman are identical with the Brahman.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=109}} While some Upanishads, acknowledges Gaudapada, imply a difference between individual soul and the Brahman, those texts are discussing the apparent distinction (duality) when one believes in apparent creation. In reality, states Gaudapada, there is no creation of souls from Brahman as they are identical.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=109}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n79/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 21-23 with footnotes</ref> We must not confuse passages meant for spiritual instruction. According to Karikas 3.17-18, Gaudapada admits that dualists disagree with this view, but the ancient texts admit duality in the context of appearances, while \"nonduality is indeed the highest reality\", translates Karmarkar.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=109}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n81/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 23-24 with footnotes 17 & 18</ref>\n\nAccording to Karl Potter's translation of Karikas 3.33-36, an awareness that is without conceptual construction is unborn, and this is identical to the object of that awareness called [[Brahman]]. This awareness is not a metaphor, nor born, it is real. Such awareness shines forth without fear, beyond words and thought, is calm and unwavering, equanimous, and full of light.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=110}}<ref name=karmarkar27>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n85/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 27-29 with footnotes</ref> This inner contactless concentration (Asparsha yoga) is difficult for most including the [[yogis]], who see fear in what is fearlessly blissful.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=110}}{{Refn|group=note|Adi Shankara interprets this Karika somewhat differently, according to Comans.{{Sfn|Michael Comans|2000|p=166}}}} Such is the awareness that comes from self-reflection, understanding, giving up attachment to ''Dukkha'' (frustration) and ''Sukha'' (pleasure), where the mind rests in indescribable calmness within.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=110}}<ref name=karmarkar29>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n85/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 29-31 with footnotes</ref>{{Refn|group=note|\u0926\u0941\u0903\u0916\u0902 \u0938\u0930\u094d\u0935\u092e\u0928\u0941\u0938\u094d\u092e\u0943\u0924\u094d\u092f \u0915\u093e\u092e\u092d\u094b\u0917\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0928\u093f\u0935\u0930\u094d\u0924\u092f\u0947\u0924\u094d \u0964 \u0905\u091c\u0902 \u0938\u0930\u094d\u0935\u092e\u0928\u0941\u0938\u094d\u092e\u0943\u0924\u094d\u092f \u091c\u093e\u0924\u0902 \u0928\u0948\u0935 \u0924\u0941 \u092a\u0936\u094d\u092f\u0924\u093f \u0965 \u096a\u0969 \u0965(...)<br />\u0928\u093e\u093d\u093d\u0938\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0926\u092f\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0938\u0941\u0916\u0902 \u0924\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0928\u093f\u0903\u0938\u0919\u094d\u0917\u0903 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u091c\u094d\u091e\u092f\u093e \u092d\u0935\u0947\u0924\u094d \u0964 \u0928\u093f\u0936\u094d\u091a\u0932\u0902 \u0928\u093f\u0936\u094d\u091a\u0930\u091a\u094d\u091a\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0924\u092e\u0947\u0915\u0940\u0915\u0941\u0930\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0924\u094d\u092a\u094d\u0930\u092f\u0924\u094d\u0928\u0924\u0903 \u0965 \u096a\u096b \u0965(...)<br />\u0938\u094d\u0935\u0938\u094d\u0925\u0902 \u0936\u093e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u0902 \u0938\u0928\u093f\u0930\u094d\u0935\u093e\u0923\u092e\u0915\u0925\u094d\u092f\u0902 \u0938\u0941\u0916\u092e\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0924\u092e\u092e\u094d \u0964 \u0905\u091c\u092e\u091c\u0947\u0928 \u091c\u094d\u091e\u0947\u092f\u0947\u0928 \u0938\u0930\u094d\u0935\u091c\u094d\u091e\u0902 \u092a\u0930\u093f\u091a\u0915\u094d\u0937\u0924\u0947 \u0965 \u096a\u096d \u0965<ref name=karmarkar29/>}}\n\n====Chapter Four: The Peace of The Firebrand (Alatasanti)====\nThe last chapter of ''Gaudapada Karika'' has a different style than the first three, and it opens by expressing reverence for all \"the greatest of men\", who are like the cosmic space through their awareness of nonduality, free from self-contradictions and confusion, and who understand [[Dharma]].{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=110}} Karikas 3\u201310 repeat some content from previous chapters, but with some word substitutions.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=111}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n89/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 32-33 with footnotes</ref> Karikas 11\u201313 quote the key duality premise of [[Samkhya]] school of Hindu philosophy, cross examines it, then asks how and why is cause eternal? The text states that the Samkhya premise \"cause is born as its effect\" leads to infinite regress, which is not persuasive.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=111}}\n\n''Gaudapada Karika'' then acknowledges the theory of [[Ajativada]] or non-origination of the ''Buddhas'' (Buddhists).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=111}} Like Samkhya premise, the text praises and cross examines it, in three ways: first, non-origination premises makes sense when neither the point of origin nor the end of something is known, but we know the point of origin of any example of something produced and there ''Ajativada'' premise does not follow; secondly, the ''Ajativada'' premise commits the ''Sadhyasama'' fallacy of reasoning by offering examples of what is yet to be proved.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=111}} Thirdly, state Karikas 29\u201341, neither [[samsara]] nor [[moksha|mukti]] has a beginning or end, because if something is born it must have an end, and something that is unborn has no end.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=112}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n97/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 39-41 with footnotes</ref>\n\nKarikas 45\u201352 state that  only (''Vijnana'') consciousness is real, explaining it with an example of fire stick before and during the time it burns, and adding we construct and deconstruct our state of awareness.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=112}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n101/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 43-44 with footnotes</ref> Karikas 53\u201356 assert that there is no causation, no effects, and repeats that consciousness is the only one real thing.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|pp=112-113}} Everything is [[impermanence|impermanent]], nothing is eternal and everything is also without origination by nature, state Karikas 57\u201360.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=113}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n103/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 45-46 with footnotes</ref>\n\nKarikas 61\u201381 repeat text on four states from earlier chapters to re-emphasize the premises about impermanence and non-origination.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=113}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n105/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 47-52 with footnotes</ref> Attachment to unreality causes desire, sorrow (Dukkha) and fear, while detachment leads to freeing from such states and to ''samadhi''.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=113}} There are three stages of understanding state Karikas 87\u201389: ''Laukika'' (ordinary. which cognizes object and subject as real), ''Shuddha laukika'' (purified ordinary, perceiving is considered real but not the objects) and ''Lokottara'' (supramundane, where neither objects nor perceiving are cognized as real).{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=113}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n111/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 53-54 with footnotes</ref>\n\nKarikas 90\u2013100 presents ''Agrayana'' (vehicle) to knowing. The text states, \"all dharmas are without beginning, without variety, and are consciousness only\".{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=113}} Duality is for the unwise, nonduality and undifferentiated Reality is for the wise and difficult to grasp. The last ''Karikas'' of the Chapter Four add, translates Karl Potter, \"this the ''Buddhas'' understand, the Buddha instructs us that consciousness does not reach the dharmas, yet the Buddha said nothing about either consciousness or dharmas!\"{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=114}}<ref>For Sanskrit original and translation: RD Karmarkar (1953), [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n113/mode/2up Gaudapada Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, Poona, pages 55-56 with footnotes</ref>\n\n===Relationship to Buddhism===\nThe influence of Buddhist doctrines on Gaudapada has been a vexed question.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}}{{Sfn|Michael Comans|2000|p=2}}\n\nOne school of scholars, such as Bhattacharya and Raju, state that Gaudapada took over the Buddhist doctrines that [[Yogacara#Representation-only|ultimate reality is pure consciousness (''vij\u00f1apti-m\u0101tra'')]]{{sfn|Raju|1971|p=177}}{{refn|group=note|It is often used interchangeably with the term ''citta-m\u0101tra'', but they have different meanings. The standard translation of both terms is \"consciousness-only\" or \"mind-only.\" Several modern researchers object this translation, and the accompanying label of \"absolute idealism\" or \"idealistic monism\".{{sfn|Kochumuttom|1999|p=1}} A better translation for ''vij\u00f1apti-m\u0101tra'' is ''representation-only''.{{sfn|Kochumuttom|1999|p=5}}}} and \"that the nature of the world is the four-cornered negation, which is the structure of M\u0101y\u0101\".{{sfn|Raju|1971|p=177}}{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|pp=126, 143-144}}{{refn|group=note|1. Something is. 2. It is not. 3. It both is and is not. 4. It neither is nor is not.{{sfn|Garfield|Priest|2003}}{{page needed|date=August 2016}} The 'four-cornered negation' is an English gloss of the Sanskrit, [[Catu\u1e63ko\u1e6di|Chatushkoti]].{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}}} Gaudapada \"wove [both doctrines] into the philosophy of ''Mandukaya Upanisad'', which was further developed by Shankara\".{{sfn|Raju|1971|p=177-178}}{{refn|group=note|The influence of [[Mahayana Buddhism]] on other religions and philosophies was not limited to Vedanta. Kalupahana notes that the [[Visuddhimagga]] \u2013 a Theravada Buddhist tradition, contains \"some metaphysical speculations, such as those of the Sarvastivadins, the Sautrantikas, and even the [[Yogacara|Yogacarins]]\".{{sfn|Kalupahana|1994|p=206}}}}\n\nOf particular interest is Chapter Four, in which according to Bhattacharya, two karikas refer to the [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] and the term ''Asparsayoga'' is borrowed from Buddhism.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}} According to Murti, \"the conclusion is irresistible that Gaudapada, a Vedanta philosopher, is attempting an advaitic interpretation of Vedanta in the light of the Madhyamika and Yogcara doctrines. He even freely quotes and appeals to them.\"<ref name=trvmurti114>TRV Murti (1955), The central philosophy of Buddhism, Routledge (2008 Reprint), {{ISBN|978-0-415-46118-4}}, pages 114-115</ref> However, adds Murti, the doctrines are unlike Buddhism. Chapter One, Two and Three are entirely Vedantin and founded on the Upanishads, with little Buddhist flavor.<ref name=trvmurti114/> While the first three chapters discuss [[Brahman]] and Atman (soul, Self), Chapter Four doesn't. This, according to Murti,<ref name=trvmurti114/> may be because this was authored by someone else and not Gaudapada, a position shared by Richard King.<ref name=iepgauda/> Further, state both Murti and King, no Vedanta scholars who followed Gaudapada ever quoted from Chapter Four, they only quote from the first three.<ref name=trvmurti114/><ref name=iepgauda/> According to Sarma, Chapter Four may well have been written by Gaudapada assuming he was fully conversant with Mahayana school's teachings, yet \"to mistake him to be a hidden or open Buddhist is absurd\".{{Sfn|Sarma|2007|pp=145-147}} The doctrines of Gaudapada and Buddhism are totally opposed, states Murti:<ref name=trvmurti114/>\n\n{{Quote|\nWe have been talking of borrowing, influence and relationship in rather general terms. It is necessary to define the possible nature of the borrowing, granting that it did take place. (...) The Vedantins stake everything on the [[Atman (Hinduism)|Atman]] (Brahman) and accept the authority of the Upanishads. We have pointed out at length the [[Anatta|Nairatmya]] standpoint of Buddhism and its total opposition to the Atman (soul, substance, the permanent and universal) in any form.\n|TRV Murti|''The Central Philosophy of Buddhism''<ref name=trvmurti116>TRV Murti (1955), The central philosophy of Buddhism, Routledge (2008 Reprint), {{ISBN|978-0-415-46118-4}}, page 116</ref>}}\n\nAdvaitins particularly have traditionally challenged the Buddhist influence thesis.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}} Modern scholarship generally accepts that Gaudapada was influenced by Buddhism, at least in terms of using Buddhist terminology to explain his ideas, but adds that Gaudapada was a Vedantin and not a Buddhist.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=105}}\n\n==Other works by Gaudapadacharya==\nA number of additional works are attributed to Gaudapada, but their authenticity is uncertain.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=104}} The attributed works are:{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=104}}{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=311}}\n* A [[bhasya]] on ''[[Brihadaranyaka Upanishad]]''\n* A bhasya on ''[[Nrisimha Tapaniya Upanishad]]''\n* A bhasya on [[Anugita]]\n* ''Durga Saptashati Tika''&nbsp;\u2014 A bhasya on [[Devi Mahatmya]]\n* ''Sri Vidyaratna Sutra'' bhasya\n* ''Subhagodaya on Sri Vidya''\n* ''Uttara Gita Bhashya''\n\nGaudapada is also credited with a commentary on ''Samkhyakarikas''. According to Potter, the naive nature of this commentary is in sharp contrast to the depth of reflection in ''Gaudapada Karikas'', and the commentary on ''Samkhyakarikas'' is unlikely to be one by Gaudapada.{{Sfn|Potter|1981|p=104}}\n\n==Advaita guru-parampar\u0101==\n{{Main|Advaita Guru Parampar\u0101}}\n\nGaudapada is one of the key persons in the Advaita Vedanta.{{Sfn|Michael Comans|2000|p=2}} He is traditionally said to have been highly influential on [[Adi Shankara]],{{sfn|Potter|1981|p=103}} one of the most important figures in Vedic philosophy.\n\n==Shri Gaudapadacharya Math==\n{{Main|Shri Gaudapadacharya Math}}\n\nShri Gaudapadacharya Math{{refn|group=note|{{lang-sa|\u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0938\u0902\u0938\u094d\u0925\u093e\u0928 \u0917\u094c\u0921\u092a\u0926\u093e\u091a\u093e\u0930\u094d\u092f \u092e\u0920}}, {{IAST|\u015ar\u012b Sansth\u0101na Gau\u1e0dapad\u0101c\u0101rya Ma\u1e6dha}}}}, also known as '''{{IAST|Kava\u1e37\u0113 ma\u1e6dha}}''' {{lang|skt|\u0915\u0935\u0933\u0947 \u092e\u0920}}, is the oldest [[matha]] of the [[South India]]n [[Saraswat Brahmin]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Shri Gowdapadacharya & Shri Kavale Math (A Commemoration volume)| page=10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shrikavalemath.org.in/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=25 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225124923/http://shrikavalemath.org.in/ |archive-date=25 December 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Peetadhipathi]] \"head monk\" is \u015ar\u012b Gau\u1e0dapad\u0101c\u0101rya. [[Rajapur Saraswat Brahmins]] and [[Smartism|Smartist]] [[Goud Saraswat Brahmin]]s are its main disciples.<ref>http://www.shrikavalemath.org.in/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181225124923/http://shrikavalemath.org.in/ |date=25 December 2018 }}, Title: About Kavale matha.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n'''List of Math'''\n*[[Kashi Math]]\n*[[Gokarna Math]]\n*[[Chitrapur Math]]\n*[[Dvaita]]\n*[[Madhwacharya]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Published sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | last =Bhatta | first =Rathnakara | year =2013 | title =Shree Shankarayana (May. 2013), pp. 190\u2013380. | url =http://www.goodreads.com/author_blog_posts/4295191-shree-shankarayana}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|author=Michael Comans|title=The Method of Early Advaita Ved\u0101nta: A Study of Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da, \u015aa\u1e45kara, Sure\u015bvara, and Padmap\u0101da|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sx12hxoFVqwC|year=2000|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|isbn=978-81-208-1722-7}}\n* {{Citation | last1 =Garfield | first1 =Jay L. | last2 =Priest | first2 =Graham | year =2003 | title =Nagarjuna and the Limits of Thought, Philosophy East & West Volume 53, Number 1 January 2003 1\u201321 | url =http://www.thezensite.com/ZenEssays/Nagarjuna/NagarjunaTheLimitsOfThought.pdf}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Isaeva|first=Natalia V. |title=From Early Vedanta to Kashmir Shaivism: Gaudapada, Bhartrhari, and Abhinavagupta|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hMCFQ39cHNkC |year=1995|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-2449-0}}\n* {{Citation | last =Kalupahana | first =David J. | year =1994 | title =A History of Buddhist Philosophy | place =Delhi | publisher =Motilal Banarsidass Publishers Private Limited}}\n* {{Citation | last =Kochumuttom | first =Thomas A. | year =1999 | title =A Buddhist Doctrine of Experience. A New Translation and Interpretation of the Works of Vasubandhu the Yogacarin | place =Delhi | publisher =Motilal Banarsidass}}\n* {{Citation | last =Nakamura | first =Hajime | year =2004 | title =A History of Early Vedanta Philosophy. Part Two | place =Delhi | publisher =Motilal Banarsidass Publishers Private Limited}}\n*{{cite book |author=Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da \u0100c\u0101rya |author2=\u015aa\u1e45kar\u0101c\u0101rya |author3=Nikhilananda, Swami |author4= V Subrahmanya Iyer  |year=1990 |title=M\u0101\u1e47\u1e0d\u016bkyopani\u1e63ad : with Gau\u1e0dap\u0101da's K\u0101rik\u0101 and Sa\u1e45kara's commentary |publisher=Advaita Ashrama |location=Calcutta |isbn=81-7505-022-5 |pages= }}\n* {{Citation | last =Potter | first =Karl. H. | year =1981 | title =''Gaudapada,'' Encyclopedia of Indian Philosophies: Advaita Ved\u0101nta up to \u015aa\u1e43kara and his pupils, Volume 3, ''pp. 103-114'' | place =Delhi | publisher = Motilal Banarsidass | isbn =81-208-0310-8}}\n* {{Citation | last =Raju | first =P.T. | year =1971 | title =The Philosophical Traditions of India | place =Delhi | publisher =Motilal Banarsidass (1992 Reprint)}}\n* {{Citation | last =Sarma | first =Chandradhar | year =2007 |isbn= 978-8120813120 | title =The Advaita Tradition in Indian Philosophy | publisher =Motilal Banarsidass}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | last =Dvivedi | first =Manilal N. | author-link=Manilal Dwivedi | year =2003 | title =The Mandukyopanishad: With Gaudapada's Karikas and the Bhashya of Sankara | publisher =Jain Publishing Company}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fox|first=Douglas|title=Dispelling the Illusion|location=Albany|publisher=SUNY Press|year=1993}}\n* {{cite book|last=Jones|first=Richard H.|title=Gaudapada: Advaita Vedanta's First Philosopher|location=New York|publisher=Jackson Square Books|year=2014}}\n* {{cite book | last =King | first =Richard | year =1995  | title =Early Advaita Vedanta and Buddhism: The Mahayana Context of the Gaudapadiya-Karika | publisher =SUNY Press}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author}}  \n* [https://www.wisdomlib.org/hinduism/book/mandukya-upanishad-karika-bhashya/index.html The Mandukya Upanishad/Karika, Shankara\u2019s Commentary and Anandagiri\u2019s Tika] Translated by Swami Nikhilananda, online ebook\n* [http://www.universaltheosophy.com/pdf-library/Mandukya%20Upanishad%20with%20Gaudapada-Karika_Johnston.pdf Gaudapada Karika], Translation and commentary by Charles Johnston, Theosophical Quarterly\n* [http://www.advaita-vedanta.org/avhp/gaudapada.html advaita-vedanta.org, ''Gaudapada'']\n* [http://www.swamij.com/upanishad-mandukya-karika.htm Mandukya Upanishad with Gaudapada's Karika]\n* [http://www.advaitayoga.org/advaitayogaarticles/karika.html P.J. Mazumdar, ''Gaudapada's Karika on the Mandukya Upanishad'']\n\n{{Hindudharma}}\n{{Indian Philosophy}}\n{{philosophy of religion}} \n{{Portal bar|Hinduism|India|Religion}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaudapada}}\n[[Category:6th-century Indian philosophers]]\n[[Category:6th-century Indian monks]]\n[[Category:Ascetics]]\n[[Category:Advaitin philosophers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Indian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Ancient Indian writers]]\n[[Category:Consequentialists]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophers]]\n[[Category:Hindu reformers]]\n[[Category:Hindu scholars]]\n[[Category:Idealists]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu monks]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu missionaries]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Indian yogis]]\n[[Category:Medieval Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Vedanta]]\n[[Category:Ontologists]]\n[[Category:Pantheists]]\n[[Category:Sanskrit writers]]\n[[Category:Indian male writers]]\n[[Category:6th-century Indian writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaudapada"}
{"title_page": "Cailleach", "text_new": "{{Cleanup lang |date=March 2019 }}\n[[File:Lightmatter cliffs of moher in County Clare Ireland.jpg|thumb|300px|right|''Ceann na Caill\u00ed'' ('The Hag's Head'), the southernmost tip of the [[Cliffs of Moher]] in [[County Clare]]. One of many locations named for the Cailleach.<ref name=\"Monaghan\">Monaghan, Patricia (2004) ''The Red-Haired Girl from the Bog: The Landscape of Celtic Myth and Spirit''. New World Library. {{ISBN|1-57731-458-1}} p.23: \"We see her silhouette on ''Ceann na Cailleach'' [recte ''Ceann na Caill\u00ed''], \"Hag's Head\", the most southerly of the [[Cliffs of Moher]]\".</ref>]]\n\nIn [[Gaels|Gaelic]] mythology ([[Irish mythology|Irish]], [[Scottish mythology|Scottish]] and [[Culture of the Isle of Man#Myth, legend and folklore|Manx]]) the {{lang|ga|'''Cailleach'''}} ({{IPA-ga|ki\u02c8l\u02b2ax; \u02c8kal\u02b2\u0259x}}, {{IPA-gd|\u02c8k\u02b0a\u028e\u0259x}}) is a divine [[hag]], a [[creator deity]], a [[weather god|weather deity]], and an ancestor deity. In modern [[Scotland|Scottish]] folklore studies she is also known as [[Beira (mythology)|Beira, Queen of Winter]]. The word literally means \"old woman, hag\", and is found with this meaning in modern [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Scottish Gaelic]],<ref name=\"dicdef\">{{cite book |last= Robertson |first= Boyd |authorlink= |author2=Ian McDonald |title= Gaelic Dictionary | publisher=  Hodder Education, Teach Yourself Series |isbn= 0-07-142667-1 |pages= 24\u201325 |year= 2004}}</ref> and has been applied to numerous mythological figures in [[Ireland]], [[Scotland]] and the [[Isle of Man]].<ref name=\"Briggs1\">Briggs, Katharine (1976) ''An Encyclopedia of Fairies''. New York, Pantheon Books. pp. 57-60.</ref>\n\n==Name==\n''Cailleach'' (\"old woman\" or \"hag\" in modern [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Scottish Gaelic]])<ref name=\"dicdef\"/><ref name=\"IrCailleach\">{{cite book |last= \u00d3 D\u00f3naill |first= Niall |authorlink= |title= Focl\u00f3ir Gaeilge-B\u00e9arla | publisher=  \u00c9ireann: Mount Salus Press |isbn= 1-85791-037-0 |page= 172 |year= 1992}}</ref> comes from the [[Old Irish|Old Gaelic]] ''Caillech'' (\"veiled one\"), an adjectival form of ''caille'' (\"veil\"), an early loan from [[Latin]] ''pallium'',<ref>Displaying the expected /p/ > /c/ change of early Latin loans in Irish.</ref> \"woollen cloak\".<ref>Rudolph Thurneysen, A grammar of old Irish, Volume 1, Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies, 1946, p. 568.</ref><ref>\u00d3 Cathasaigh, T. 'The eponym of Cnogba', \u00c9igse 23, 1989, pp. 27\u201338.</ref><ref>\u00d3 h\u00d3g\u00e1in, D. Myth, legend & romance: an encyclopaedia of the Irish folk tradition, Prentice Hall Press, 1991, p. 67.</ref><ref name=\"Macbain\">Macbain, Alexander (1998) ''Etymological Dictionary Of Scottish-Gaelic''. New York, Hippocrene Books. {{ISBN|0-7818-0632-1}} p. 63.</ref>\n\nThe Cailleach is often referred to as the ''Cailleach Bh\u00e9ara(ch)'' (in Scottish Gaelic ''Cailleach Bheurra'' or ''A' Chailleach Bheurrach'' or variations thereof. Gear\u00f3id \u00d3 Crualaoich attributes twin meanings to the name; the legendary context of cow goddess, or association with horned beasts, and a folklore attribution as a word meaning \"sharp, shrill, inimical\" \u2013 ''bior(ach)'' or ''beur(ach)'' \u2013 and refers to the Cailleach's association with winter and wilderness.<ref name=\"\u00d3 Crualaoich\">{{cite book |first=Gear\u00f3id |last=\u00d3 Crualaoich |year=2006 |title=The Book of the Cailleach: Stories of the Wise-Woman Healer |publisher=Cork University Press |isbn =1-85918-372-7}}</ref>\n\nThe 8th/9th-century Irish poem ''The Lament of the Old Woman'' says that the Cailleach's name is ''Digdi'' or ''Digde''. In ''The Hunt of [[Slieve Gullion|Slieve Cuilinn]]'' she is called ''Milucra'', sister of [[\u00c1ine]]. In the tale of the [[Glas Gaibhnenn]] she is called ''Bir\u00f3g''. Elsewhere, she is called ''Bu\u00ed'' or ''Bua(ch)''.<ref>\u00d3 Cathasaigh, Tom\u00e1s. [http://www.carrowkeel.com/sites/boyne/knowth2a.html \"Knowth - The Epynom of Cnogba\"].</ref> In [[Manx language|Manx Gaelic]] she is known as the ''Caillagh''.<ref name=\"Briggs1\"/><ref>Monaghan, Patricia. ''The Encyclopedia of Celtic Mythology and Folklore''. Infobase Publishing, 2004. p.69</ref>\n\nThe plural of ''cailleach'' is {{lang|ga|cailleacha}} ({{IPA-ga|ki\u02c8l\u02b2ax\u0259; \u02c8kal\u02b2\u0259x\u0259}}) in Irish, {{lang|gd|cailleachan}} ({{IPA-gd|\u02c8k\u02b0a\u028e\u0259x\u0259n}}) in Scottish Gaelic and ''caillaghyn'' in Manx.  The word is found as a component in terms like the Gaelic ''cailleach-dhubh'' (\"nun\") and ''cailleach-oidhche'' (\"[[owl]]\"),<ref name=\"dicdef\"/> as well as the Irish ''cailleach feasa'' (\"wise woman, fortune-teller\") and ''cailleach phiseogach'' (\"sorceress, charm-worker\"). Related words include the Gaelic ''caileag'' and the Irish ''cail\u00edn'' (\"young woman, girl, colleen\"), the diminutive of ''caile'' \"woman\"<ref name=\"dicdef\"/> and the [[Scots language|Lowland Scots]] ''carline''/''[[Carlin stone|carlin]]'' (\"old woman, witch\").<ref name=\"RossD\">{{cite book |last= Ross |first= Davie |title= Scots-English English-Scots Dictionary |publisher= New York: Hippocrene Pres |isbn= 0-7818-0779-4 |page= [https://archive.org/details/scotsenglishengl0000unse/page/21 21] |year= 1999 |author2= Gavin D. Smith |url= https://archive.org/details/scotsenglishengl0000unse/page/21 }}</ref>  A more obscure word that is sometimes interpreted as \"hag\" is the Irish ''s\u00edle'', which has led some to speculate on a connection between the Cailleach and the stonecarvings of [[Sheela na Gig]]s.<ref name=\"RossA\">Ross, Anne (1973, reprint 2004) \"The divine hag of the pagan Celts\" in ''The Witch Figure: Folklore Essays by a Group of Scholars in England Honoring the 75th Birthday of Katharine M. Briggs''. ed. by Venetia Newall. London, Routledge and Kegan Paul. {{ISBN|0-415-33074-2}}.</ref>\n\n==Legends==\n[[File:Cruachan.jpg|thumb|300px|left|[[Ben Cruachan]], highest point in [[Argyll and Bute]], home of the ''Cailleach nan Cruachan'']]\nIn [[Scotland]], where she is also known as [[Beira (mythology)|Beira, Queen of Winter]] (a name given by 20th-century folklorist [[Donald Alexander Mackenzie]]), she is credited with making numerous mountains and large hills, which are said to have been formed when she was striding across the land and accidentally dropped rocks from her creel or wicker basket. In other cases she is said to have built the mountains intentionally, to serve as her stepping stones. She carries a hammer for shaping the hills and valleys, and is said to be the mother of all the goddesses and gods.<ref name=\"Mackenzie\">Mackenzie, Donald Alexander (1917).    \"[http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/celt/tsm/tsm04.htm Beira, Queen of Winter]\"  in ''Wonder Tales from Scottish Myth and Legend\".</ref>\n\nThe Cailleach displays several traits befitting the personification of winter: she herds [[deer]], she fights spring, and her staff freezes the ground.<ref name=\"Briggs2\">{{cite book |first=K. M. |last=Briggs |year=1967 |title=The Fairies in English Tradition and Literature |page=40 |publisher=University of Chicago Press}}</ref>\n\nIn partnership with the goddess [[Brigid|Br\u00ecghde]], the Cailleach is seen as a seasonal deity or spirit, ruling the winter months between [[Samhain]]n (1 November or first day of winter) and [[Beltane|Bealltainn]] (1 May or first day of summer), while Br\u00ecghde rules the summer months between Bealltainn and Samhainn.<ref name=\"McNeill\">{{cite book |first=F. Marian |last=McNeill |year=1959 |title=The Silver Bough, Vol.2: A Calendar of Scottish National Festivals, Candlemas to Harvest Home |pages=20\u201321 |publisher=William MacLellan |isbn=0-85335-162-7}}</ref> Some interpretations have the Cailleach and Br\u00ecghde as two faces of the same goddess,<ref name=\"McNeill\"/> while others describe the Cailleach as turning to [[Carlin stone|stone]] on Bealltainn and reverting to humanoid form on Samhainn in time to rule over the winter months. Depending on local climate, the transfer of power between the winter goddess and the summer goddess is celebrated any time between [[Imbolc|L\u00e0 Fh\u00e8ill Br\u00ecghde]] (1 February) at the earliest, Latha na Cailliche (25 March), or Bealltainn (1 May) at the latest, and the local festivals marking the arrival of the first signs of spring may be named after either the Cailleach or Br\u00ecghde.<ref name=\"McNeill\"/>\n\n[[Imbolc|L\u00e0 Fh\u00e8ill Br\u00ecghde]] is also the day the Cailleach gathers her firewood for the rest of the winter. Legend has it that if she intends to make the winter last a good while longer, she will make sure the weather on 1 February is bright and sunny, so she can gather plenty of firewood to keep herself warm in the coming months.<ref name=\"Briggs1\"/> As a result, people are generally relieved if L\u00e0 Fh\u00e8ill Br\u00ecghde is a day of foul weather, as it means the Cailleach is asleep, will soon run out of firewood, and therefore winter is almost over.<ref name=\"Briggs1\"/>  On the Isle of Man, where She is known as ''Caillagh ny Groamagh'', the Cailleach is said to have been seen on [[Imbolc|St. Bride's day]] in the form of a gigantic bird, carrying sticks in her beak.<ref name=\"Briggs1\"/>\n\nIn Scotland, the Cailleachan (lit. 'old women') are also known as The Storm Hags, and seen as personifications of the elemental powers of nature, especially in a destructive aspect. They are said to be particularly active in raising the windstorms of spring, during the period known as ''A' Chailleach''.<ref name=\"McNeill\"/><ref name=\"McNeill2\">{{cite book |first=F. Marian |last=McNeill |year=1959 |title=The Silver Bough, Vol.1: Scottish Folklore and Folk-Belief |page=119 |publisher=William MacLellan |isbn=0-85335-161-9}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Corryvreckan.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The Corryvreckan whirlpool ([[Scottish Gaelic]]: ''Coire Bhreacain'' - 'whirlpool/cauldron of the plaid') washtub of the Cailleach]]\nOn the west coast of Scotland, the Cailleach ushers in winter by washing her [[History of the kilt#The great kilt|great plaid]] ([[Scottish Gaelic|Gaelic]]: ''f\u00e9ileadh m\u00f2r'') in the [[Gulf of Corryvreckan]] ([[Scottish Gaelic|Gaelic]]: ''Coire Bhreacain'' - 'whilrpool/cauldron of the plaid'). This process is said to take three days, during which the roar of the coming tempest is heard as far away as {{convert|20|mi|km|spell=in}} inland. When she is finished, her plaid is pure white and snow covers the land.<ref name=\"McNeill\"/>\n\nIn Scotland and Ireland, the first farmer to finish the grain harvest made a [[corn dolly]], representing the Cailleach (also called \"the Carlin or Carline\"<ref>Frazer, ''[[The Golden Bough]]'' 1922, ch. 45.</ref>), from the last sheaf of the crop. The figure would then be tossed into the field of a neighbor who had not yet finished bringing in their grain. The last farmer to finish had the responsibility to take in and care for the corn dolly for the next year, with the implication they'd have to feed and house the hag all winter. Competition was fierce to avoid having to take in the Old Woman.<ref name=\"McNeill3\">McNeill, Vol.2 (1959) pp. 119-124.</ref>\n\nSome scholars believe the Old Irish poem, \"[[The Hag of Beara|The Lament of the Old Woman of Beara]]\" is about the Cailleach; [[Kuno Meyer]] states, \"she had fifty foster-children in Beare. She had seven periods of youth one after another, so that every man who had lived with her came to die of old age, and her grandsons and great-grandsons were tribes and races.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Kuno |last=Meyer |year=1994 |origyear=1913 |title=Ancient Irish Poetry |pages=[https://archive.org/details/ancientirishpoet00kuno/page/90 90\u201393] |publisher=Constable and Co. |isbn=0-09-473380-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/ancientirishpoet00kuno/page/90 }}</ref><ref name=\"\u00d3 Crualaoich2\">{{cite book |first=Gear\u00f3id |last=\u00d3 Crualaoich |year=2006 |title=The Book of the Cailleach: Stories of the Wise-Woman Healer |pages=48\u201352 |publisher=Cork University Press |isbn =1-85918-372-7}}</ref>\n\n==Locations associated with the Cailleach==\n[[Image:Summit of Slieve na Calliagh.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The burial chamber at the summit of ''Sliabh na Caill\u00ed'']]\n\n===Ireland===\nIn [[Ireland]] she is also associated with craggy, prominent mountains and outcroppings, such as Hag's Head ({{Irish place name|Ceann Caill\u00ed|hag's head}}) the southernmost tip of the [[Cliffs of Moher]] in [[County Clare]].<ref name=\"Monaghan\"/>\n\nThe megalithic tombs at [[Loughcrew]] in [[County Meath]] are situated atop [[Slieve na Calliagh]] ({{Irish place name|Sliabh na Caill\u00ed|the hag's mountain}}) and include a kerbstone known as \"the hag's chair\".<ref name=hagschair>Cochrane, Andrew (2005) \"[http://www.knowth.com/loughcrew-cochrane4.htm A taste of the unexpected: subverting mentalit\u00e9s through the motifs and settings of Irish passage tombs]\". p.4: \"To the north of Cairn T and on the exterior is located K29 or the \u2018Hag\u2019s Chair\u2019. This kerbstone has visual imagery on its front and back face. The top of the central part of this kerbstone is believed to be artificially cut to create the chair appearance (Shee Twohig 1981, 217; contra. Conwell 1866, 371)\".</ref> Cairn T on Slieve na Calliagh is a classic [[passage tomb]], in which the rays of the [[equinox]] sunrise shine down the passageway and illuminate an inner chamber filled with megalithic stonecarvings.<ref name=knowth2>Documented in [http://www.knowth.com/loughcrew-equinox.htm photos and videos taken on site for six years running].</ref>\n\nThe summit of [[Slieve Gullion]] in [[County Armagh]] features a passage tomb known locally as the 'Calliagh Beara's House'. There is also a lake, where the Calliagh is said to have played a trick on the mythical warrior, [[Fionn mac Cumhaill]], when he took on the physical appearance of an old man after diving into the lake to retrieve a ring that the Calliagh fooled him into thinking was lost. <ref>https://www.ringofgullion.org/stories/the-calliagh-berras-lake/</ref> \n\n[[Aillenacally]] (''Aill na Caill\u00ed'', \"Hag Cliff\") is a [[cliff]] in [[County Galway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/en/18159?s=Aill+na+Caill%C3%AD|title=Aill na Caill\u00ed/Aillenacally|author=|date=|website=Logainm.ie}}</ref> \n\nThe passage tombs on the C\u00fail Iorra peninsula in [[County Sligo]], are associated with the Cailleach (one is called the Cailleach a Bh\u00e9rra's House<ref name=cailleachhouse>Meehan, Padraig. Listoghil, A Seasonal Alignment, 2014, Gungho Publications,</ref>). [[William Butler Yeats]] refers to the Sligo Cailleach as the 'Clooth na Bare'.<ref name=clooth>Jeffares, Alexander Norman. A Commentary on the Collected Poems of W.B. Yeats, 1968, Stanford University Press</ref>\n\n===Scotland===\n[[File:Loch Awe.jpg|thumb|190px|left|Loch Awe ([[Scottish Gaelic]], ''Loch Obha''), created by ''Cailleach nan Cruachan'']]\nThe Cailleach is prominent in the landscape of [[Argyll and Bute]], Scotland. In later tales she is known as the ''Cailleach nan Cruachan'' (\"the witch of [[Ben Cruachan]]\"). Ben Cruachan is the tallest mountain in the region. Tea-towels and postcards of her are sold in the visitor shop for the [[Ben Cruachan|Hollow Mountain]], which also features a mural depicting her accidental creation of [[Loch Awe]].<ref name=\"LegendCruachan\">'[http://www.visitcruachan.co.uk/about/history.asp The Legend of Cruachan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028132707/http://www.visitcruachan.co.uk/about/history.asp |date=2007-10-28 }}', from the Ben Cruachan visitor's website. Access date 21-11-2007.</ref>\n\nLegend has it that the Cailleach was tired from a long day herding deer. Atop Ben Cruachan she fell asleep on her watch and a well she was tending overflowed, running down from the highlands and flooding the valleys below, forming first a [[river]] and then the [[loch]].<ref name=\"LegendCruachan\"/><ref name=\"MysteriousBritain\">'[http://www.mysteriousbritain.co.uk/folklore/calleach.html Cailleach Bheur] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061009222651/http://www.mysteriousbritain.co.uk/folklore/calleach.html |date=2006-10-09 }}' from the ''Mysterious Britain'' website. Access date 21-11-2007.</ref> The overflowing well is a common motif in local [[Gaels|Gaelic]] creation tales - as seen in the goddess [[Boann]]'s similar creation of the [[River Boyne]] in Ireland.<ref name=\"McKillopBoann\">MacKillop, James (1998) ''Dictionary of Celtic Mythology''. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|0-19-280120-1}} p. 45.</ref> Other connections to the region include her above-mentioned strong ties with the fierce whirlpool in the [[Gulf of Corryvreckan]].<ref name=\"McNeill\"/>\n\n[[Beinn na Caillich (Red Hills)|Beinn na Caillich]] on the [[Isle of Skye]] is one of her haunts, as are [[Beinn na Caillich (Kyle Rhea)|other mountains]] prominent in the landscape, and from which fierce storms of sleet and rain descend, wreaking havoc and destruction upon the lands below.<ref name=\"McNeill\"/>\n\n[[File:Tighnacailleach.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Tigh nan Cailleach, near [[Glen Lyon]] in Perthshire, Scotland]]There is a Gleann Cailliche in [[Glen Lyon]] in Perthshire with a stream named Allt Cailliche which runs into [[Loch Lyon]]. This area is famous for a pagan ritual which according to legend is associated to the Cailleach. There is a small [[Shieling|shieling]] in the Glen, known as either Tigh nan Cailleach (Scottish Gaelic for ''house of the old women''<ref name=\"MacLennan\">MacLennan, Malcolm, ''Gaelic Dictionary'', Acair and Aberdeen University Press, 1985 photolithographic reprint of 1st edition, 1925</ref>)  or Tigh nam Bodach, (Scottish Gaelic for ''house of the old men''<ref name=\"MacLennan\"/>), which houses a number of heavy water-worn stones, resembling miniature human beings.<ref name=\"McK\">McKerracher, Archie, ''Perthshire in History and Legend'', 1st edition 1988, John Donald Publishers, {{ISBN|0859762238}}, pp55-56</ref> Roughly rectangular, the building originally measured 2m by 1.3m by 0.4m high with a stone roof.<ref>''National Record of the Historic Environment'' (Canmore), ''Tigh Nam Bodach'', ''Archaeology Notes'', https://canmore.org.uk/site/23898/tigh-nam-bodach</ref>  A replacement roof of a wooden pallet having collapsed and the whole building having become somewhat ruinous it was rebuilt by a local dyker in 2011.<ref>''Tigh nam Bodach stones of Glen Cailliche get makeover from dyking expert'', ''Daily Record'', 11 May 2012, https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/tigh-nam-bodach-stones-glen-2729865</ref> \n\nAccording to local legend the stones represent the Cailleach, her husband the Bodach, and their children<ref name=\"RossAnne\">{{cite book | first =Anne | last = Ross | year =2000| title =Folklore of the Scottish Highlands | chapter = | editor = | others = | edition = | pages =114 | publisher =Tempus Publishing Ltd | location =Stroud| id = | url = }}</ref><ref name=\"StonesInSun\">''Sacred stones out in the sun'', ''Daily Record'', 4 May 2012, https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/sacred-stones-out-sun-2729746</ref> and the site may represent the only surviving shrine of its kind in Great Britain.<ref name =\"McK\"/>The local legend suggests that the Cailleach and her family were given shelter in the glen by the locals and while they stayed there the glen was always fertile and prosperous. When they left they gave the stones to the locals with the promise that as long as the stones were put out to look over the glen at [[Beltane|Bealltainn]] and put back into the shelter and made secure for the winter at [[Samhain]]n then the glen would continue to be fertile.<ref name=\"RossAnne\"/>\n\nThis ritual is still carried out to this day.<ref name=\"StonesInSun\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Baba Yaga]]\n* [[Banshee]]\n* [[Beira (mythology)|Beira]]\n* [[Bodach]]\n* [[Carlin stone]]\n* [[Carrauntoohil]]\n* [[Celtic animism]]\n* [[Cyhyraeth]]\n* [[Imbolc]]\n* [[Sheela na Gig]]\n* [[Slieve Gullion]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*[[Carmina Gadelica|Carmichael, Alexander]] (1992). ''Carmina Gadelica''. Lindisfarne Press. {{ISBN|0-940262-50-9}}\n*[[John Gregorson Campbell|Campbell, John Gregorson]] (1900, 1902, 2005) ''The Gaelic Otherworld''. Edited by Ronald Black. Edinburgh, Birlinn Ltd. {{ISBN|1-84158-207-7}}\n*[[Kevin Danaher|Danaher, Kevin]] (1962). ''The Year in Ireland''. Irish Books & Media. {{ISBN|0-937702-13-7}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Hull |first=Eleanor |title=Legends and traditions of the Cailleach Bheara or Old Woman (Hag) of Beare |journal=Folklore |volume=38 | issue = 3 |date=30 Sep 1927 |pages=225\u201354 |jstor=1256390 |doi=10.1080/0015587x.1927.9718387}}\n*MacKillop, James (1998). ''Dictionary of Celtic Mythology''. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|0-19-280120-1}}\n*[[F. Marian McNeill|McNeill, F. Marian]] (1959). ''The Silver Bough, Vol. 1 -4''. William MacLellan, Glasgow\n*{{Cite book |last=Monaghan |first=Patricia |year=2004 |title=Encyclopedia of Celtic Myth and Folklore |location=New York |publisher=Facts on File |isbn=0-8160-4524-0 }}\n*{{Cite book |last=\u00d3 Crualaoich |first=Gear\u00f3id |year=2003 |title=The Book of the Cailleach: Stories of the Wise-Woman Healer |location=Cork |publisher=Cork UP |isbn=1-85918-372-7 }}\n*{{Cite book |last=Ross |first=Anne |year=2000 |title=Folklore of the Scottish Highlands |location=Stroud |publisher=Tempus Publishing Ltd |isbn=0-7524-1904-8 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Primary sources==\n*\"The Lament of the Old Woman of Beare\", ed. and tr. {{Cite encyclopedia |author=Donncha \u00d3 hAodha |year=1989 |title=The Lament of the Old Woman of Beare |encyclopedia=Sages, Saints and Storytellers: Celtic studies in Honour of Professor James Carney |editor=Donnchadh \u00d3 Corr\u00e1in, Liam Breatnach and Kim McCone |series=Maynooth Monographs 2 |location=Maynooth |publisher=An Sagart |pages=308\u201331 }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite journal |last=Krappe |first=A. H. |year=1936 |title=La Cailleach Bheara. Notes de mythologie Ga\u00e9lique |journal=[[\u00c9tudes Celtiques]] |volume=1 |pages=292\u2013302 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Carey |first=John |author-link=John Carey (Celticist) |title=Transmutations of Immortality in 'The Lament of the Old Woman of Beare' |journal=Celtica |volume=23 |year=1999|url=http://www.celt.dias.ie/publications/celtica/c23/c23-30.pdf |pages=30\u20137 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HQI3RCUFuYE&index=5&list=PLOhjfSlRDZPdp_352RmC4Wb0NqmglVl-a ''An Cailleach Bh\u00e9arra'' (2007)] - an [[Irish Film Board|IFB]] [[short film]] (8 minutes)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120209125300/http://www.visitcruachan.co.uk/about/history.asp Ben Cruachan, the Hollow Mountain] - The Legend of Cruachan, featuring the Cailleach Bheur\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071124210331/http://www.rte.ie/radio1/hagsqueensandwisewomen/ Hags, Queens and Wise Women: Supernatural Females of the Irish Otherworld] - RT\u00c9 radio series, based on the work of Gear\u00f3id \u00d3 Crualaoich\n*[http://www.knowth.com/loughcrew-cochrane4.htm Photos of the Hag's Chair] and other megalithic features at Slieve na Calliagh, Ireland\n*[http://www.irishcultureandcustoms.com/ACustom/AfterHarvest.html Putting out the hare, putting on the harvest knots] - don't get stuck with the Cailleach\n\n{{good article}}\n{{Celtic mythology (Mythological)}}\n{{Celtic mythology (Scottish)}}\n{{National personifications}}\n\n[[Category:Creator goddesses]]\n[[Category:Destroyer goddesses]]\n[[Category:Irish goddesses]]\n[[Category:Scottish folklore]]\n[[Category:Scottish mythology]]\n[[Category:Personifications of Ireland]]\n[[Category:National personifications]]\n[[Category:Celtic deities]]\n", "text_old": "{{Cleanup lang |date=March 2019 }}\n[[File:Lightmatter cliffs of moher in County Clare Ireland.jpg|thumb|300px|right|''Ceann na Caill\u00ed'' ('The Hag's Head'), the southernmost tip of the [[Cliffs of Moher]] in [[County Clare]]. One of many locations named for the Cailleach.<ref name=\"Monaghan\">Monaghan, Patricia (2004) ''The Red-Haired Girl from the Bog: The Landscape of Celtic Myth and Spirit''. New World Library. {{ISBN|1-57731-458-1}} p.23: \"We see her silhouette on ''Ceann na Cailleach'' [recte ''Ceann na Caill\u00ed''], \"Hag's Head\", the most southerly of the [[Cliffs of Moher]]\".</ref>]]\n\nIn [[Gaels|Gaelic]] mythology ([[Irish mythology|Irish]], [[Scottish mythology|Scottish]] and [[Culture of the Isle of Man#Myth, legend and folklore|Manx]]) the {{lang|ga|'''Cailleach'''}} ({{IPA-ga|ki\u02c8l\u02b2ax; \u02c8kal\u02b2\u0259x}}, {{IPA-gd|\u02c8k\u02b0a\u028e\u0259x}}) is a divine [[hag]], a [[creator deity]], a [[weather god|weather deity]], and an ancestor deity. In modern [[Scotland|Scottish]] folklore studies she is also known as [[Beira (mythology)|Beira, Queen of Winter]]. The word literally means \"old woman, hag\", and is found with this meaning in modern [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Scottish Gaelic]],<ref name=\"dicdef\">{{cite book |last= Robertson |first= Boyd |authorlink= |author2=Ian McDonald |title= Gaelic Dictionary | publisher=  Hodder Education, Teach Yourself Series |isbn= 0-07-142667-1 |pages= 24\u201325 |year= 2004}}</ref> and has been applied to numerous mythological figures in [[Ireland]], [[Scotland]] and the [[Isle of Man]].<ref name=\"Briggs1\">Briggs, Katharine (1976) ''An Encyclopedia of Fairies''. New York, Pantheon Books. pp. 57-60.</ref>\n\n==Name==\n''Cailleach'' (\"old woman\" or \"hag\" in modern [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Scottish Gaelic]])<ref name=\"dicdef\"/><ref name=\"IrCailleach\">{{cite book |last= \u00d3 D\u00f3naill |first= Niall |authorlink= |title= Focl\u00f3ir Gaeilge-B\u00e9arla | publisher=  \u00c9ireann: Mount Salus Press |isbn= 1-85791-037-0 |page= 172 |year= 1992}}</ref> comes from the [[Old Irish|Old Gaelic]] ''Caillech'' (\"veiled one\"), an adjectival form of ''caille'' (\"veil\"), an early loan from [[Latin]] ''pallium'',<ref>Displaying the expected /p/ > /c/ change of early Latin loans in Irish.</ref> \"woollen cloak\".<ref>Rudolph Thurneysen, A grammar of old Irish, Volume 1, Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies, 1946, p. 568.</ref><ref>\u00d3 Cathasaigh, T. 'The eponym of Cnogba', \u00c9igse 23, 1989, pp. 27\u201338.</ref><ref>\u00d3 h\u00d3g\u00e1in, D. Myth, legend & romance: an encyclopaedia of the Irish folk tradition, Prentice Hall Press, 1991, p. 67.</ref><ref name=\"Macbain\">Macbain, Alexander (1998) ''Etymological Dictionary Of Scottish-Gaelic''. New York, Hippocrene Books. {{ISBN|0-7818-0632-1}} p. 63.</ref>\n\nThe Cailleach is often referred to as the ''Cailleach Bh\u00e9ara(ch)'' (in Scottish Gaelic ''Cailleach Bheurra'' or ''A' Chailleach Bheurrach'' or variations thereof. Gear\u00f3id \u00d3 Crualaoich attributes twin meanings to the name; the legendary context of cow goddess, or association with horned beasts, and a folklore attribution as a word meaning \"sharp, shrill, inimical\" \u2013 ''bior(ach)'' or ''beur(ach)'' \u2013 and refers to the Cailleach's association with winter and wilderness.<ref name=\"\u00d3 Crualaoich\">{{cite book |first=Gear\u00f3id |last=\u00d3 Crualaoich |year=2006 |title=The Book of the Cailleach: Stories of the Wise-Woman Healer |publisher=Cork University Press |isbn =1-85918-372-7}}</ref>\n\nThe 8th/9th-century Irish poem ''The Lament of the Old Woman'' says that the Cailleach's name is ''Digdi'' or ''Digde''. In ''The Hunt of [[Slieve Gullion|Slieve Cuilinn]]'' she is called ''Milucra'', sister of [[\u00c1ine]]. In the tale of the [[Glas Gaibhnenn]] she is called ''Bir\u00f3g''. Elsewhere, she is called ''Bu\u00ed'' or ''Bua(ch)''.<ref>\u00d3 Cathasaigh, Tom\u00e1s. [http://www.carrowkeel.com/sites/boyne/knowth2a.html \"Knowth - The Epynom of Cnogba\"].</ref> In [[Manx language|Manx Gaelic]] she is known as the ''Caillagh''.<ref name=\"Briggs1\"/><ref>Monaghan, Patricia. ''The Encyclopedia of Celtic Mythology and Folklore''. Infobase Publishing, 2004. p.69</ref>\n\nThe plural of ''cailleach'' is {{lang|ga|cailleacha}} ({{IPA-ga|ki\u02c8l\u02b2ax\u0259; \u02c8kal\u02b2\u0259x\u0259}}) in Irish, {{lang|gd|cailleachan}} ({{IPA-gd|\u02c8k\u02b0a\u028e\u0259x\u0259n}}) in Scottish Gaelic and ''caillaghyn'' in Manx.  The word is found as a component in terms like the Gaelic ''cailleach-dhubh'' (\"nun\") and ''cailleach-oidhche'' (\"[[owl]]\"),<ref name=\"dicdef\"/> as well as the Irish ''cailleach feasa'' (\"wise woman, fortune-teller\") and ''cailleach phiseogach'' (\"sorceress, charm-worker\"). Related words include the Gaelic ''caileag'' and the Irish ''cail\u00edn'' (\"young woman, girl, colleen\"), the diminutive of ''caile'' \"woman\"<ref name=\"dicdef\"/> and the [[Scots language|Lowland Scots]] ''carline''/''[[Carlin stone|carlin]]'' (\"old woman, witch\").<ref name=\"RossD\">{{cite book |last= Ross |first= Davie |title= Scots-English English-Scots Dictionary |publisher= New York: Hippocrene Pres |isbn= 0-7818-0779-4 |page= [https://archive.org/details/scotsenglishengl0000unse/page/21 21] |year= 1999 |author2= Gavin D. Smith |url= https://archive.org/details/scotsenglishengl0000unse/page/21 }}</ref>  A more obscure word that is sometimes interpreted as \"hag\" is the Irish ''s\u00edle'', which has led some to speculate on a connection between the Cailleach and the stonecarvings of [[Sheela na Gig]]s.<ref name=\"RossA\">Ross, Anne (1973, reprint 2004) \"The divine hag of the pagan Celts\" in ''The Witch Figure: Folklore Essays by a Group of Scholars in England Honoring the 75th Birthday of Katharine M. Briggs''. ed. by Venetia Newall. London, Routledge and Kegan Paul. {{ISBN|0-415-33074-2}}.</ref>\n\n==Legends==\n[[File:Cruachan.jpg|thumb|300px|left|[[Ben Cruachan]], highest point in [[Argyll and Bute]], home of the ''Cailleach nan Cruachan'']]\nIn [[Scotland]], where she is also known as [[Beira (mythology)|Beira, Queen of Winter]] (a name given by 20th-century folklorist [[Donald Alexander Mackenzie]]), she is credited with making numerous mountains and large hills, which are said to have been formed when she was striding across the land and accidentally dropped rocks from her creel or wicker basket. In other cases she is said to have built the mountains intentionally, to serve as her stepping stones. She carries a hammer for shaping the hills and valleys, and is said to be the mother of all the goddesses and gods.<ref name=\"Mackenzie\">Mackenzie, Donald Alexander (1917).    \"[http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/celt/tsm/tsm04.htm Beira, Queen of Winter]\"  in ''Wonder Tales from Scottish Myth and Legend\".</ref>\n\nThe Cailleach displays several traits befitting the personification of winter: she herds [[deer]], she fights spring, and her staff freezes the ground.<ref name=\"Briggs2\">{{cite book |first=K. M. |last=Briggs |year=1967 |title=The Fairies in English Tradition and Literature |page=40 |publisher=University of Chicago Press}}</ref>\n\nIn partnership with the goddess [[Brigid|Br\u00ecghde]], the Cailleach is seen as a seasonal deity or spirit, ruling the winter months between [[Samhain]]n (1 November or first day of winter) and [[Beltane|Bealltainn]] (1 May or first day of summer), while Br\u00ecghde rules the summer months between Bealltainn and Samhainn.<ref name=\"McNeill\">{{cite book |first=F. Marian |last=McNeill |year=1959 |title=The Silver Bough, Vol.2: A Calendar of Scottish National Festivals, Candlemas to Harvest Home |pages=20\u201321 |publisher=William MacLellan |isbn=0-85335-162-7}}</ref> Some interpretations have the Cailleach and Br\u00ecghde as two faces of the same goddess,<ref name=\"McNeill\"/> while others describe the Cailleach as turning to [[Carlin stone|stone]] on Bealltainn and reverting to humanoid form on Samhainn in time to rule over the winter months. Depending on local climate, the transfer of power between the winter goddess and the summer goddess is celebrated any time between [[Imbolc|L\u00e0 Fh\u00e8ill Br\u00ecghde]] (1 February) at the earliest, Latha na Cailliche (25 March), or Bealltainn (1 May) at the latest, and the local festivals marking the arrival of the first signs of spring may be named after either the Cailleach or Br\u00ecghde.<ref name=\"McNeill\"/>\n\n[[Imbolc|L\u00e0 Fh\u00e8ill Br\u00ecghde]] is also the day the Cailleach gathers her firewood for the rest of the winter. Legend has it that if she intends to make the winter last a good while longer, she will make sure the weather on 1 February is bright and sunny, so she can gather plenty of firewood to keep herself warm in the coming months.<ref name=\"Briggs1\"/> As a result, people are generally relieved if L\u00e0 Fh\u00e8ill Br\u00ecghde is a day of foul weather, as it means the Cailleach is asleep, will soon run out of firewood, and therefore winter is almost over.<ref name=\"Briggs1\"/>  On the Isle of Man, where She is known as ''Caillagh ny Groamagh'', the Cailleach is said to have been seen on [[Imbolc|St. Bride's day]] in the form of a gigantic bird, carrying sticks in her beak.<ref name=\"Briggs1\"/>\n\nIn Scotland, the Cailleachan (lit. 'old women') are also known as The Storm Hags, and seen as personifications of the elemental powers of nature, especially in a destructive aspect. They are said to be particularly active in raising the windstorms of spring, during the period known as ''A' Chailleach''.<ref name=\"McNeill\"/><ref name=\"McNeill2\">{{cite book |first=F. Marian |last=McNeill |year=1959 |title=The Silver Bough, Vol.1: Scottish Folklore and Folk-Belief |page=119 |publisher=William MacLellan |isbn=0-85335-161-9}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Corryvreckan.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The Corryvreckan whirlpool ([[Scottish Gaelic]]: ''Coire Bhreacain'' - 'whirlpool/cauldron of the plaid') washtub of the Cailleach]]\nOn the west coast of Scotland, the Cailleach ushers in winter by washing her [[History of the kilt#The great kilt|great plaid]] ([[Scottish Gaelic|Gaelic]]: ''f\u00e9ileadh m\u00f2r'') in the [[Gulf of Corryvreckan]] ([[Scottish Gaelic|Gaelic]]: ''Coire Bhreacain'' - 'whilrpool/cauldron of the plaid'). This process is said to take three days, during which the roar of the coming tempest is heard as far away as {{convert|20|mi|km|spell=in}} inland. When she is finished, her plaid is pure white and snow covers the land.<ref name=\"McNeill\"/>\n\nIn Scotland and Ireland, the first farmer to finish the grain harvest made a [[corn dolly]], representing the Cailleach (also called \"the Carlin or Carline\"<ref>Frazer, ''[[The Golden Bough]]'' 1922, ch. 45.</ref>), from the last sheaf of the crop. The figure would then be tossed into the field of a neighbor who had not yet finished bringing in their grain. The last farmer to finish had the responsibility to take in and care for the corn dolly for the next year, with the implication they'd have to feed and house the hag all winter. Competition was fierce to avoid having to take in the Old Woman.<ref name=\"McNeill3\">McNeill, Vol.2 (1959) pp. 119-124.</ref>\n\nSome scholars believe the Old Irish poem, \"[[The Hag of Beara|The Lament of the Old Woman of Beara]]\" is about the Cailleach; [[Kuno Meyer]] states, \"she had fifty foster-children in Beare. She had seven periods of youth one after another, so that every man who had lived with her came to die of old age, and her grandsons and great-grandsons were tribes and races.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Kuno |last=Meyer |year=1994 |origyear=1913 |title=Ancient Irish Poetry |pages=[https://archive.org/details/ancientirishpoet00kuno/page/90 90\u201393] |publisher=Constable and Co. |isbn=0-09-473380-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/ancientirishpoet00kuno/page/90 }}</ref><ref name=\"\u00d3 Crualaoich2\">{{cite book |first=Gear\u00f3id |last=\u00d3 Crualaoich |year=2006 |title=The Book of the Cailleach: Stories of the Wise-Woman Healer |pages=48\u201352 |publisher=Cork University Press |isbn =1-85918-372-7}}</ref>\n\n==Locations associated with the Cailleach==\n[[Image:Summit of Slieve na Calliagh.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The burial chamber at the summit of ''Sliabh na Caill\u00ed'']]\n\n===Ireland===\nIn [[Ireland]] she is also associated with craggy, prominent mountains and outcroppings, such as Hag's Head ({{Irish place name|Ceann Caill\u00ed|hag's head}}) the southernmost tip of the [[Cliffs of Moher]] in [[County Clare]].<ref name=\"Monaghan\"/>\n\nThe megalithic tombs at [[Loughcrew]] in [[County Meath]] are situated atop [[Slieve na Calliagh]] ({{Irish place name|Sliabh na Caill\u00ed|the hag's mountain}}) and include a kerbstone known as \"the hag's chair\".<ref name=hagschair>Cochrane, Andrew (2005) \"[http://www.knowth.com/loughcrew-cochrane4.htm A taste of the unexpected: subverting mentalit\u00e9s through the motifs and settings of Irish passage tombs]\". p.4: \"To the north of Cairn T and on the exterior is located K29 or the \u2018Hag\u2019s Chair\u2019. This kerbstone has visual imagery on its front and back face. The top of the central part of this kerbstone is believed to be artificially cut to create the chair appearance (Shee Twohig 1981, 217; contra. Conwell 1866, 371)\".</ref> Cairn T on Slieve na Calliagh is a classic [[passage tomb]], in which the rays of the [[equinox]] sunrise shine down the passageway and illuminate an inner chamber filled with megalithic stonecarvings.<ref name=knowth2>Documented in [http://www.knowth.com/loughcrew-equinox.htm photos and videos taken on site for six years running].</ref>\n\nThe summit of [[Slieve Gullion]] in [[County Armagh]] features a passage tomb known locally as the 'the Calliagh Beara's House'. There is also a lake, where the Calliagh is said to have played a trick on the mythical warrior, [[Fionn mac Cumhaill]], when he took on the physical appearance of an old man after diving into the lake to retrieve a ring that the Calliagh fooled him into thinking was lost. <ref>https://www.ringofgullion.org/stories/the-calliagh-berras-lake/</ref> \n\n[[Aillenacally]] (''Aill na Caill\u00ed'', \"Hag Cliff\") is a [[cliff]] in [[County Galway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/en/18159?s=Aill+na+Caill%C3%AD|title=Aill na Caill\u00ed/Aillenacally|author=|date=|website=Logainm.ie}}</ref> \n\nThe passage tombs on the C\u00fail Iorra peninsula in [[County Sligo]], are associated with the Cailleach (one is called the Cailleach a Bh\u00e9rra's House<ref name=cailleachhouse>Meehan, Padraig. Listoghil, A Seasonal Alignment, 2014, Gungho Publications,</ref>). [[William Butler Yeats]] refers to the Sligo Cailleach as the 'Clooth na Bare'.<ref name=clooth>Jeffares, Alexander Norman. A Commentary on the Collected Poems of W.B. Yeats, 1968, Stanford University Press</ref>\n\n===Scotland===\n[[File:Loch Awe.jpg|thumb|190px|left|Loch Awe ([[Scottish Gaelic]], ''Loch Obha''), created by ''Cailleach nan Cruachan'']]\nThe Cailleach is prominent in the landscape of [[Argyll and Bute]], Scotland. In later tales she is known as the ''Cailleach nan Cruachan'' (\"the witch of [[Ben Cruachan]]\"). Ben Cruachan is the tallest mountain in the region. Tea-towels and postcards of her are sold in the visitor shop for the [[Ben Cruachan|Hollow Mountain]], which also features a mural depicting her accidental creation of [[Loch Awe]].<ref name=\"LegendCruachan\">'[http://www.visitcruachan.co.uk/about/history.asp The Legend of Cruachan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028132707/http://www.visitcruachan.co.uk/about/history.asp |date=2007-10-28 }}', from the Ben Cruachan visitor's website. Access date 21-11-2007.</ref>\n\nLegend has it that the Cailleach was tired from a long day herding deer. Atop Ben Cruachan she fell asleep on her watch and a well she was tending overflowed, running down from the highlands and flooding the valleys below, forming first a [[river]] and then the [[loch]].<ref name=\"LegendCruachan\"/><ref name=\"MysteriousBritain\">'[http://www.mysteriousbritain.co.uk/folklore/calleach.html Cailleach Bheur] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061009222651/http://www.mysteriousbritain.co.uk/folklore/calleach.html |date=2006-10-09 }}' from the ''Mysterious Britain'' website. Access date 21-11-2007.</ref> The overflowing well is a common motif in local [[Gaels|Gaelic]] creation tales - as seen in the goddess [[Boann]]'s similar creation of the [[River Boyne]] in Ireland.<ref name=\"McKillopBoann\">MacKillop, James (1998) ''Dictionary of Celtic Mythology''. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|0-19-280120-1}} p. 45.</ref> Other connections to the region include her above-mentioned strong ties with the fierce whirlpool in the [[Gulf of Corryvreckan]].<ref name=\"McNeill\"/>\n\n[[Beinn na Caillich (Red Hills)|Beinn na Caillich]] on the [[Isle of Skye]] is one of her haunts, as are [[Beinn na Caillich (Kyle Rhea)|other mountains]] prominent in the landscape, and from which fierce storms of sleet and rain descend, wreaking havoc and destruction upon the lands below.<ref name=\"McNeill\"/>\n\n[[File:Tighnacailleach.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Tigh nan Cailleach, near [[Glen Lyon]] in Perthshire, Scotland]]There is a Gleann Cailliche in [[Glen Lyon]] in Perthshire with a stream named Allt Cailliche which runs into [[Loch Lyon]]. This area is famous for a pagan ritual which according to legend is associated to the Cailleach. There is a small [[Shieling|shieling]] in the Glen, known as either Tigh nan Cailleach (Scottish Gaelic for ''house of the old women''<ref name=\"MacLennan\">MacLennan, Malcolm, ''Gaelic Dictionary'', Acair and Aberdeen University Press, 1985 photolithographic reprint of 1st edition, 1925</ref>)  or Tigh nam Bodach, (Scottish Gaelic for ''house of the old men''<ref name=\"MacLennan\"/>), which houses a number of heavy water-worn stones, resembling miniature human beings.<ref name=\"McK\">McKerracher, Archie, ''Perthshire in History and Legend'', 1st edition 1988, John Donald Publishers, {{ISBN|0859762238}}, pp55-56</ref> Roughly rectangular, the building originally measured 2m by 1.3m by 0.4m high with a stone roof.<ref>''National Record of the Historic Environment'' (Canmore), ''Tigh Nam Bodach'', ''Archaeology Notes'', https://canmore.org.uk/site/23898/tigh-nam-bodach</ref>  A replacement roof of a wooden pallet having collapsed and the whole building having become somewhat ruinous it was rebuilt by a local dyker in 2011.<ref>''Tigh nam Bodach stones of Glen Cailliche get makeover from dyking expert'', ''Daily Record'', 11 May 2012, https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/tigh-nam-bodach-stones-glen-2729865</ref> \n\nAccording to local legend the stones represent the Cailleach, her husband the Bodach, and their children<ref name=\"RossAnne\">{{cite book | first =Anne | last = Ross | year =2000| title =Folklore of the Scottish Highlands | chapter = | editor = | others = | edition = | pages =114 | publisher =Tempus Publishing Ltd | location =Stroud| id = | url = }}</ref><ref name=\"StonesInSun\">''Sacred stones out in the sun'', ''Daily Record'', 4 May 2012, https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/sacred-stones-out-sun-2729746</ref> and the site may represent the only surviving shrine of its kind in Great Britain.<ref name =\"McK\"/>The local legend suggests that the Cailleach and her family were given shelter in the glen by the locals and while they stayed there the glen was always fertile and prosperous. When they left they gave the stones to the locals with the promise that as long as the stones were put out to look over the glen at [[Beltane|Bealltainn]] and put back into the shelter and made secure for the winter at [[Samhain]]n then the glen would continue to be fertile.<ref name=\"RossAnne\"/>\n\nThis ritual is still carried out to this day.<ref name=\"StonesInSun\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Baba Yaga]]\n* [[Banshee]]\n* [[Beira (mythology)|Beira]]\n* [[Bodach]]\n* [[Carlin stone]]\n* [[Carrauntoohil]]\n* [[Celtic animism]]\n* [[Cyhyraeth]]\n* [[Imbolc]]\n* [[Sheela na Gig]]\n* [[Slieve Gullion]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*[[Carmina Gadelica|Carmichael, Alexander]] (1992). ''Carmina Gadelica''. Lindisfarne Press. {{ISBN|0-940262-50-9}}\n*[[John Gregorson Campbell|Campbell, John Gregorson]] (1900, 1902, 2005) ''The Gaelic Otherworld''. Edited by Ronald Black. Edinburgh, Birlinn Ltd. {{ISBN|1-84158-207-7}}\n*[[Kevin Danaher|Danaher, Kevin]] (1962). ''The Year in Ireland''. Irish Books & Media. {{ISBN|0-937702-13-7}}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Hull |first=Eleanor |title=Legends and traditions of the Cailleach Bheara or Old Woman (Hag) of Beare |journal=Folklore |volume=38 | issue = 3 |date=30 Sep 1927 |pages=225\u201354 |jstor=1256390 |doi=10.1080/0015587x.1927.9718387}}\n*MacKillop, James (1998). ''Dictionary of Celtic Mythology''. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|0-19-280120-1}}\n*[[F. Marian McNeill|McNeill, F. Marian]] (1959). ''The Silver Bough, Vol. 1 -4''. William MacLellan, Glasgow\n*{{Cite book |last=Monaghan |first=Patricia |year=2004 |title=Encyclopedia of Celtic Myth and Folklore |location=New York |publisher=Facts on File |isbn=0-8160-4524-0 }}\n*{{Cite book |last=\u00d3 Crualaoich |first=Gear\u00f3id |year=2003 |title=The Book of the Cailleach: Stories of the Wise-Woman Healer |location=Cork |publisher=Cork UP |isbn=1-85918-372-7 }}\n*{{Cite book |last=Ross |first=Anne |year=2000 |title=Folklore of the Scottish Highlands |location=Stroud |publisher=Tempus Publishing Ltd |isbn=0-7524-1904-8 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Primary sources==\n*\"The Lament of the Old Woman of Beare\", ed. and tr. {{Cite encyclopedia |author=Donncha \u00d3 hAodha |year=1989 |title=The Lament of the Old Woman of Beare |encyclopedia=Sages, Saints and Storytellers: Celtic studies in Honour of Professor James Carney |editor=Donnchadh \u00d3 Corr\u00e1in, Liam Breatnach and Kim McCone |series=Maynooth Monographs 2 |location=Maynooth |publisher=An Sagart |pages=308\u201331 }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite journal |last=Krappe |first=A. H. |year=1936 |title=La Cailleach Bheara. Notes de mythologie Ga\u00e9lique |journal=[[\u00c9tudes Celtiques]] |volume=1 |pages=292\u2013302 }}\n*{{Cite journal |last=Carey |first=John |author-link=John Carey (Celticist) |title=Transmutations of Immortality in 'The Lament of the Old Woman of Beare' |journal=Celtica |volume=23 |year=1999|url=http://www.celt.dias.ie/publications/celtica/c23/c23-30.pdf |pages=30\u20137 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HQI3RCUFuYE&index=5&list=PLOhjfSlRDZPdp_352RmC4Wb0NqmglVl-a ''An Cailleach Bh\u00e9arra'' (2007)] - an [[Irish Film Board|IFB]] [[short film]] (8 minutes)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120209125300/http://www.visitcruachan.co.uk/about/history.asp Ben Cruachan, the Hollow Mountain] - The Legend of Cruachan, featuring the Cailleach Bheur\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071124210331/http://www.rte.ie/radio1/hagsqueensandwisewomen/ Hags, Queens and Wise Women: Supernatural Females of the Irish Otherworld] - RT\u00c9 radio series, based on the work of Gear\u00f3id \u00d3 Crualaoich\n*[http://www.knowth.com/loughcrew-cochrane4.htm Photos of the Hag's Chair] and other megalithic features at Slieve na Calliagh, Ireland\n*[http://www.irishcultureandcustoms.com/ACustom/AfterHarvest.html Putting out the hare, putting on the harvest knots] - don't get stuck with the Cailleach\n\n{{good article}}\n{{Celtic mythology (Mythological)}}\n{{Celtic mythology (Scottish)}}\n{{National personifications}}\n\n[[Category:Creator goddesses]]\n[[Category:Destroyer goddesses]]\n[[Category:Irish goddesses]]\n[[Category:Scottish folklore]]\n[[Category:Scottish mythology]]\n[[Category:Personifications of Ireland]]\n[[Category:National personifications]]\n[[Category:Celtic deities]]\n", "name_user": "Ira Leviton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted a duplicate \"the\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cailleach"}
{"title_page": "Who Goes There! (play)", "text_new": "{{Infobox play\n| name              =  Who Goes There!\n| image             =\n| image_size        =\n| caption           =\n| writer            = [[John Dighton]] \n| setting           =\n| date of premiere  = 11 September 1950\n| original language = English\n| place             = [[Theatre Royal, Windsor]]\n| series            = \n| subject           = \n| genre             = Comedy\n}}\n'''''Who Goes There!''''' is a 1950 [[comedy play]] by the British writer [[John Dighton]]. The action takes place entirely around [[St James's Palace]].\n\nIt premiered at the [[Theatre Royal, Windsor]] in September 1950. It then ran for 222 performances in London's [[West End theatre|West End]] between 4 April and 13 October 1951, initially at the [[Vaudeville Theatre]] before transferring to the [[Duke of York's Theatre]]. The cast included [[Nigel Patrick]], [[Beatrice Campbell]], [[Anthony Sharp]], [[Trevor Reid]], [[Frances Rowe]] and [[Geraldine McEwan]], making her West End debut.<ref>Wearing p.84</ref>\n\n==Adaptation==\nIn 1952 it was adapted into a [[Who Goes There!|film of the same title]] directed by [[Anthony Kimmins]] and starring [[Nigel Patrick]], reprising his stage role, [[Valerie Hobson]] and [[George Cole (actor)|George Cole]].<ref>Goble p.128</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Goble, Alan. ''The Complete Index to Literary Sources in Film''. Walter de Gruyter, 1999.\n* Wearing, J.P. ''The London Stage 1950-1959: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel''.  Rowman & Littlefield, 2014.\n\n[[Category:1950 plays]]\n[[Category:Plays by John Dighton]]\n[[Category:British plays]]\n[[Category:West End plays]]\n[[Category:Comedy plays]]\n[[Category:Plays set in London]]\n[[Category:British plays adapted into films]]\n\n{{1950s-play-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox play\n| name              =  Who Goes There!\n| image             =\n| image_size        =\n| caption           =\n| writer            = [[John Dighton]] \n| setting           =\n| date of premiere  = 11 September 1950\n| original language = English\n| place             = [[Theatre Royal, Windsor]]\n| series            = \n| subject           = \n| genre             = Comedy\n}}\n'''''Who Goes There!''''' is a 1950 [[comedy play]] by the British writer [[John Dighton]]. The action takes place entirely around [[St James's Palace]].\n\nIt premiered at the [[Theatre Royal, Windsor]] in September 1950. It then ran for 222 performances in London's [[West End theatre|West End]] between 4 April and 13 October 1951, initially at the [[Vaudeville Theatre]] before transferring to the [[Duke of York's Theatre]]. The cast included [[Nigel Patrick]], [[Beatrice Campbell]], [[Anthony Sharp]], [[Trevor Reid]], [[Frances Rowe]] and [[Geraldine McEwan]], making her West End debut.<ref>Wearing p.84</ref>\n\n==Adaptation==\nIn 1952 it was adapted into a [[Who Goes There!|film of the same title]] directed by [[Anthony Kimmins]] and starring [[Nigel Patrick]], reprising his stage role, [[Valerie Hobson]] and [[George Cole]].<ref>Goble p.128</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Goble, Alan. ''The Complete Index to Literary Sources in Film''. Walter de Gruyter, 1999.\n* Wearing, J.P. ''The London Stage 1950-1959: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel''.  Rowman & Littlefield, 2014.\n\n[[Category:1950 plays]]\n[[Category:Plays by John Dighton]]\n[[Category:British plays]]\n[[Category:West End plays]]\n[[Category:Comedy plays]]\n[[Category:Plays set in London]]\n[[Category:British plays adapted into films]]\n\n{{1950s-play-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGeorge Cole(link changed toGeorge Cole (actor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Who_Goes_There!_(play)"}
